394
00:26:47.400 --> 00:26:50.600
My Dionyza, shall we rest us here,

395
00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:54.100
And by relating tales of others' griefs,

396
00:26:54.100 --> 00:26:56.870
See if 'twill teach us to forget our own?

397
00:26:56.870 --> 00:27:01.500
That were to blow at fire in hope to quench it;

398
00:27:01.500 --> 00:27:03.930
For who digs hills because they do aspire

399
00:27:03.930 --> 00:27:08.130
Throws down one mountain to cast up a higher.

400
00:27:08.130 --> 00:27:14.230
O my distressed lord, even such our griefs are;

401
00:27:14.230 --> 00:27:17.130
Here they're but felt, and seen with mischief's eyes,

402
00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:20.970
But like to groves, being topp'd, they higher rise.

403
00:27:20.970 --> 00:27:22.430
O Dionyza,

404
00:27:22.430 --> 00:27:25.400
Who wanteth food, and will not say he wants it,

405
00:27:25.400 --> 00:27:28.300
Or can conceal his hunger till he famish?

406
00:27:28.300 --> 00:27:31.470
Our tongues and sorrows force us to sound deep

407
00:27:31.470 --> 00:27:35.470
Our woes into the air; our eyes do weep,

408
00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:39.300
Till tongues fetch breath that may proclaim them louder;

409
00:27:39.300 --> 00:27:42.900
That, if heaven slumber while their creatures want,

410
00:27:42.900 --> 00:27:46.570
They may awake their helps to comfort them.

411
00:27:49.330 --> 00:27:56.030
I'll then discourse our woes, felt several years,

412
00:27:56.030 --> 00:28:00.770
And wanting breath to speak help me with tears.

413
00:28:00.770 --> 00:28:04.600
I'll do my best, sir.

414
00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:09.130
This Tarsus, o'er which I have the government,

415
00:28:09.130 --> 00:28:12.600
A city on whom plenty held full hand,

416
00:28:12.600 --> 00:28:16.770
For riches strew'd herself even in the streets;

417
00:28:16.770 --> 00:28:20.730
Whose towers bore heads so high they kiss'd the clouds,

418
00:28:20.730 --> 00:28:23.530
And strangers ne'er beheld but wondered at;

419
00:28:23.530 --> 00:28:27.300
Whose men and dames so jetted and adorn'd,

420
00:28:27.300 --> 00:28:30.370
Like one another's glass to trim them by:

421
00:28:30.370 --> 00:28:33.130
Their tables were stored full, to glad the sight,

422
00:28:33.130 --> 00:28:36.000
And not so much to feed on as delight;

423
00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:42.170
All poverty was scorn'd, and pride so great,

424
00:28:42.170 --> 00:28:45.470
The name of help grew odious to repeat.

425
00:28:45.470 --> 00:28:47.770
O, 'tis too true.

426
00:28:47.770 --> 00:28:50.600
But see what heaven can do! By this our change,

427
00:28:50.600 --> 00:28:54.170
These mouths, who but of late, earth, sea, and air,

428
00:28:54.170 --> 00:28:56.330
Were all too little to content and please,

429
00:28:56.330 --> 00:28:59.200
Although they gave their creatures in abundance,

430
00:28:59.200 --> 00:29:01.030
As houses are defiled for want of use,

431
00:29:01.030 --> 00:29:04.500
They are now starved for want of exercise:

432
00:29:04.500 --> 00:29:07.930
Those palates who, not yet two summers younger,

433
00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:11.870
Must have inventions to delight the taste,

434
00:29:11.870 --> 00:29:15.270
Would now be glad of bread, and beg for it:

435
00:29:15.270 --> 00:29:17.230
Those mothers who, to nousle up their babes,

436
00:29:17.230 --> 00:29:20.370
Thought nought too curious, are ready now

437
00:29:20.370 --> 00:29:22.830
To eat those little darlings whom they loved.

438
00:29:22.830 --> 00:29:25.470
So sharp are hunger's teeth, that man and wife

439
00:29:25.470 --> 00:29:29.430
Draw lots who first shall die to lengthen life:

440
00:29:29.430 --> 00:29:32.770
Here stands a lord, and there a lady weeping;

441
00:29:32.770 --> 00:29:35.470
Here many sink, yet those which see them fall

442
00:29:35.470 --> 00:29:40.570
Have scarce strength left to give them burial.

443
00:29:40.570 --> 00:29:42.270
Is not this true?

444
00:29:42.270 --> 00:29:45.770
Our cheeks and hollow eyes do witness it.

445
00:29:45.770 --> 00:29:48.800
O, let those cities that of plenty's cup

446
00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:51.370
And her prosperities so largely taste,

447
00:29:51.370 --> 00:30:00.170
With their superfluous riots, hear these tears!

448
00:30:00.170 --> 00:30:04.700
The misery of Tarsus may be theirs.

449
00:30:08.970 --> 00:30:10.570
Where's the lord governor?

450
00:30:10.570 --> 00:30:11.700
Here.

451
00:30:11.700 --> 00:30:14.600
Speak out thy sorrows which thou bring'st in haste,

452
00:30:14.600 --> 00:30:16.930
For comfort is too far for us to expect.

453
00:30:16.930 --> 00:30:19.570
We have descried, upon our neighbouring shore,

454
00:30:19.570 --> 00:30:23.330
A portly sail of ships make hitherward.

455
00:30:23.330 --> 00:30:24.830
I thought as much.

456
00:30:24.830 --> 00:30:27.030
One sorrow never comes but brings an heir,

457
00:30:27.030 --> 00:30:29.270
That may succeed as his inheritor;

458
00:30:29.270 --> 00:30:32.670
And so in ours: some neighbouring nation,

459
00:30:32.670 --> 00:30:35.570
Taking advantage of our misery,

460
00:30:35.570 --> 00:30:39.270
Hath stuff'd these hollow vessels with their power,

461
00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:42.930
To beat us down, the which are down already;

462
00:30:42.930 --> 00:30:49.100
And make a conquest of unhappy me,

463
00:30:49.100 --> 00:30:51.400
That's the least fear; for, by the semblance

464
00:30:51.400 --> 00:30:55.830
Of their white flags display'd, they bring us peace,

465
00:30:55.830 --> 00:31:00.170
And come to us as favourers, not as foes.

466
00:31:00.170 --> 00:31:02.530
Thou speak'st like him's untutor'd to repeat:

467
00:31:02.530 --> 00:31:05.330
Who makes the fairest show means most deceit.

468
00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:08.070
But bring they what they will and what they can,

469
00:31:08.070 --> 00:31:09.470
What need we fear?

470
00:31:09.470 --> 00:31:14.600
The ground's the lowest, and we are half way there.

471
00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:16.530
Go tell their general we attend him here,

472
00:31:16.530 --> 00:31:18.800
To know for what he comes, and whence he comes,

473
00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:20.030
And what he craves.

474
00:31:20.030 --> 00:31:21.630
I go, my lord.

475
00:31:21.630 --> 00:31:27.300
Welcome is peace, if he on peace consist;

476
00:31:27.300 --> 00:31:31.700
If wars, we are unable to resist.

477
00:31:31.700 --> 00:31:38.100
(â™ª music)

478
00:31:38.100 --> 00:31:42.830
Lord governor, for so we hear you are,

479
00:31:42.830 --> 00:31:44.870
Let not our ships and number of our men

480
00:31:44.870 --> 00:31:48.300
Be like a beacon fired to amaze your eyes.

481
00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:51.130
We have heard your miseries as far as Tyre,

482
00:31:51.130 --> 00:31:56.200
And seen the desolation of your streets:

483
00:31:56.200 --> 00:31:58.600
Nor come we to add sorrow to your hearts,

484
00:31:58.600 --> 00:32:01.670
But to relieve them of their heavy load;

485
00:32:01.670 --> 00:32:03.430
And these our ships, you happily may think

486
00:32:03.430 --> 00:32:05.770
Are like the Trojan horse was stuff'd within

487
00:32:05.770 --> 00:32:08.770
With bloody veins, expecting overthrow,

488
00:32:08.770 --> 00:32:13.270
Are stored with corn to make your needy bread,

489
00:32:13.270 --> 00:32:16.870
And give them life whom hunger starved half dead.

490
00:32:16.870 --> 00:32:19.100
The gods of Greece protect you!

491
00:32:19.100 --> 00:32:21.000
And we'll pray for you.

492
00:32:22.930 --> 00:32:35.230
Arise, I pray you, rise:

493
00:32:37.100 --> 00:32:41.870
We do not look for reverence, but for love,

494
00:32:41.870 --> 00:32:45.430
And harbourage for ourself, our ships, and men.

495
00:32:45.430 --> 00:32:50.470
The which when any shall not gratify,

496
00:32:50.470 --> 00:32:53.930
Or pay you with unthankfulness in thought,

497
00:32:53.930 --> 00:33:02.000
Be it our wives, our children, or ourselves,

498
00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:06.470
The curse of heaven and men succeed their evils!

499
00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:09.670
Till when,--the which I hope shall ne'er be seen,--

500
00:33:09.670 --> 00:33:15.800
Your grace is welcome to our town and us.

501
00:33:15.800 --> 00:33:19.130
Which welcome we'll accept; feast here awhile,

502
00:33:19.130 --> 00:33:24.900
Until our stars that frown lend us a smile.

503
00:33:26.030 --> 00:33:30.270
