504
00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:46.300
Here have you seen a mighty king

505
00:33:46.300 --> 00:33:49.930
His child, I wis, to incest bring;

506
00:33:49.930 --> 00:33:52.630
A better prince and benign lord,

507
00:33:52.630 --> 00:33:58.200
That will prove awful both in deed and word.

508
00:33:58.200 --> 00:34:00.970
Be quiet then as men should be,

509
00:34:00.970 --> 00:34:03.070
Till he hath pass'd necessity.

510
00:34:03.070 --> 00:34:04.900
I'll show you those in troubles reign,

511
00:34:04.900 --> 00:34:08.830
Losing a mite, a mountain gain.

512
00:34:08.830 --> 00:34:10.130
The good in conversation,

513
00:34:10.130 --> 00:34:11.400
To whom I give my benison,

514
00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:14.230
Is still at Tarsus, where each man

515
00:34:14.230 --> 00:34:17.870
Thinks all is writ he spoken can;

516
00:34:17.870 --> 00:34:19.270
And, to remember what he does,

517
00:34:19.270 --> 00:34:22.930
Build his statue to make him glorious:

518
00:34:25.570 --> 00:34:26.730
But tidings to the contrary

519
00:34:26.730 --> 00:34:31.000
Are brought your eyes; what need speak I?

520
00:34:33.730 --> 00:34:36.270
Good Helicane, hath stay'd at home,

521
00:34:36.270 --> 00:34:38.100
Not to eat honey like a drone

522
00:34:38.100 --> 00:34:41.470
From others' labours; for though he strive

523
00:34:41.470 --> 00:34:44.370
To killen bad, keep good alive;

524
00:34:44.370 --> 00:34:46.200
And to fulfil his prince' desire,

525
00:34:46.200 --> 00:34:48.700
Sends word of all that haps in Tyre:

526
00:34:48.700 --> 00:34:51.330
How Thaliard came full bent with sin

527
00:34:51.330 --> 00:34:54.200
And had intent to murder him;

528
00:34:54.200 --> 00:34:56.530
And that in Tarsus was not best

529
00:34:56.530 --> 00:35:01.430
Longer for him to make his rest.

530
00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:05.430
He, doing so, put forth to seas,

531
00:35:05.430 --> 00:35:08.400
Where when men been, there's seldom ease;

532
00:35:08.400 --> 00:35:11.000
For now the wind begins to blow;

533
00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.030
Thunder above and deeps below

534
00:35:13.030 --> 00:35:15.470
Make such unquiet, that the ship

535
00:35:15.470 --> 00:35:19.270
Should house him safe is wreck'd and split;

536
00:35:19.270 --> 00:35:21.930
And he, good prince, having all lost,

537
00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:25.530
By waves from coast to coast is tost:

538
00:35:25.530 --> 00:35:27.730
All perishen of man, of pelf,

539
00:35:27.730 --> 00:35:31.630
Ne aught escapen but himself;

540
00:35:31.630 --> 00:35:34.800
Till fortune, tired with doing bad,

541
00:35:34.800 --> 00:35:38.570
Threw him ashore, to give him glad:

542
00:35:38.570 --> 00:35:42.670
And here he comes. What shall be next,

543
00:35:42.670 --> 00:35:47.170
Pardon old Gower,--this longs the text.

544
00:35:53.930 --> 00:35:58.000
Yet cease your ire, you angry stars of heaven!

545
00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:02.670
Wind, rain, and thunder, remember, earthly man

546
00:36:02.670 --> 00:36:06.300
Is but a substance that must yield to you;

547
00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:11.600
And I, as fits my nature, do obey you:

548
00:36:19.830 --> 00:36:24.600
Alas, the sea hath cast me on the rocks,

549
00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:27.730
Wash'd me from shore to shore, and left me breath

550
00:36:27.730 --> 00:36:33.130
Nothing to think on but ensuing death:

551
00:36:33.130 --> 00:36:35.030
Let it suffice the greatness of your powers

552
00:36:35.030 --> 00:36:38.900
To have bereft a prince of all his fortunes;

553
00:36:38.900 --> 00:36:40.900
And having thrown him from your watery grave,

554
00:36:40.900 --> 00:36:48.370
Here to have death in peace is all he'll crave.

555
00:36:51.800 --> 00:36:56.130
What, ho, Pilch!

556
00:36:56.130 --> 00:37:00.100
Ha, come and bring away the nets!

557
00:37:00.100 --> 00:37:04.200
What, Patch-breech, I say!

558
00:37:04.200 --> 00:37:06.070
What say you, master?

559
00:37:06.070 --> 00:37:08.200
Look how thou stirrest now! come away, or I'll

560
00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:09.670
fetch thee with a wanion.

561
00:37:09.670 --> 00:37:13.600
Faith, master, I am thinking of the poor men that

562
00:37:13.600 --> 00:37:17.470
were cast away before us even now.

563
00:37:17.470 --> 00:37:20.970
Alas, poor souls, it grieved my heart to hear what

564
00:37:20.970 --> 00:37:23.300
pitiful cries they made to us to help them, when,

565
00:37:23.300 --> 00:37:25.700
well-a-day, we could scarce help ourselves.

566
00:37:25.700 --> 00:37:27.330
Nay, master, said not I as much when I saw the

567
00:37:27.330 --> 00:37:31.570
porpus how he bounced and tumbled? they say

568
00:37:31.570 --> 00:37:36.070
they're half fish, half flesh: a plague on them,

569
00:37:36.070 --> 00:37:39.900
they ne'er come but I look to be washed. Master, I

570
00:37:39.900 --> 00:37:43.430
marvel how the fishes live in the sea.

571
00:37:43.430 --> 00:37:46.700
Why, as men do a-land; the great ones eat up the

572
00:37:46.700 --> 00:37:49.830
little ones: I can compare your rich misers to

573
00:37:49.830 --> 00:37:53.270
nothing so fitly as to a whale; a' plays and

574
00:37:53.270 --> 00:37:55.700
tumbles, driving the poor fry before him, and at

575
00:37:55.700 --> 00:37:58.900
last devours them all at a mouthful: such whales

576
00:37:58.900 --> 00:38:01.900
have I heard on o' the land, who never leave gaping

577
00:38:01.900 --> 00:38:05.330
till they've swallowed the whole parish, church,

578
00:38:05.330 --> 00:38:08.370
steeple, bells, and all.

579
00:38:08.370 --> 00:38:09.900
A pretty moral.

580
00:38:09.900 --> 00:38:12.130
But, master, if I had been the sexton,

581
00:38:12.130 --> 00:38:14.630
I would have been that day in the belfry.

582
00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:16.000
Why, man?

583
00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:19.800
Because he should have swallowed me too: and when I

584
00:38:19.800 --> 00:38:22.170
had been in his belly, I would have kept such a

585
00:38:22.170 --> 00:38:24.570
jangling of the bells, that he should never have left,

586
00:38:24.570 --> 00:38:27.830
till he cast bells, steeple, church,

587
00:38:27.830 --> 00:38:32.000
and parish up again. But if the good King Simonides

588
00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:33.930
were of my mind,--

589
00:38:33.930 --> 00:38:35.000
Simonides!

590
00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.130
We would purge the land of these drones, that rob

591
00:38:37.130 --> 00:38:39.330
the bee of her honey.

592
00:38:39.330 --> 00:38:40.970
How from the finny subject of the sea

593
00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:44.930
These fishers tell the infirmities of men;

594
00:38:44.930 --> 00:38:46.370
And from their watery empire recollect

595
00:38:46.370 --> 00:38:50.500
All that may men approve or men detect!

596
00:39:01.430 --> 00:39:03.900
Peace be at your labour, honest fishermen.

597
00:39:03.900 --> 00:39:07.500
Honest! good fellow, what's that? If it be a day fits you,

598
00:39:07.500 --> 00:39:12.430
search out of the calendar, and nobody look after it.

599
00:39:12.430 --> 00:39:14.600
May see the sea hath cast upon your coast.

600
00:39:14.600 --> 00:39:18.100
What a drunken knave was the sea to cast thee in our way!

601
00:39:18.100 --> 00:39:19.800
A man whom both the waters and the wind,

602
00:39:19.800 --> 00:39:23.370
In that vast tennis-court, have made the ball

603
00:39:23.370 --> 00:39:30.730
For them to play upon, entreats you pity him:

604
00:39:33.270 --> 00:39:36.100
He asks of you, that never used to beg.

605
00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:40.400
No, friend, cannot you beg? Here's them in our

606
00:39:40.400 --> 00:39:43.130
land of Greece gets more with begging

607
00:39:43.130 --> 00:39:45.630
than we can get with working.

608
00:39:45.630 --> 00:39:47.970
Canst thou catch any fishes, then?

609
00:39:47.970 --> 00:39:49.670
I never practised it.

610
00:39:49.670 --> 00:39:51.870
Nay, then thou wilt starve, sure; for here's nothing

611
00:39:51.870 --> 00:39:55.430
to be got now-a-days, unless thou canst fish for't.

612
00:39:55.430 --> 00:39:58.900
What I have been I have forgot to know;

613
00:39:58.900 --> 00:40:05.100
But what I am, want teaches me to think on:

614
00:40:05.100 --> 00:40:11.600
A man throng'd up with cold: my veins are chill,

615
00:40:11.600 --> 00:40:14.400
And have no more of life than may suffice

616
00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:18.330
To give my tongue that heat to ask your help;

617
00:40:18.330 --> 00:40:20.400
Which if you shall refuse, when I am dead,

618
00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:24.470
For that I am a man, pray see me buried.

619
00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:30.230
Die quoth-a? Now gods forbid! I have a coat here;

620
00:40:30.230 --> 00:40:36.400
come, put it on; keep thee warm. Now, afore me,

621
00:40:36.400 --> 00:40:39.300
a handsome fellow! Come, thou shalt go home,

622
00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:40.970
and we'll have flesh for holidays,

623
00:40:40.970 --> 00:40:44.030
fish for fasting-days, and moreo'er puddings

624
00:40:44.030 --> 00:40:46.670
and flap-jacks, and thou shalt be welcome.

625
00:40:46.670 --> 00:40:48.670
I thank you, sir.

626
00:40:48.670 --> 00:40:50.800
Hark you, my friend; you said you could not beg.

627
00:40:50.800 --> 00:40:53.130
I did but crave.

628
00:40:53.130 --> 00:40:55.700
But crave! Then I'll turn craver too, and so I

629
00:40:55.700 --> 00:40:57.400
shall 'scape whipping.

630
00:40:57.400 --> 00:40:59.070
Why, are all your beggars whipped, then?

631
00:40:59.070 --> 00:41:01.430
O, not all, my friend, not all; for if all your

632
00:41:01.430 --> 00:41:04.230
beggars were whipped, I would wish no better office

633
00:41:04.230 --> 00:41:10.800
than to be beadle. But, master, I'll go draw up the net.

634
00:41:13.270 --> 00:41:16.200
How well this honest mirth becomes their labour!

635
00:41:16.200 --> 00:41:20.730
Hark you, friend, do you know where ye are?

636
00:41:20.730 --> 00:41:21.900
Not well.

637
00:41:21.900 --> 00:41:28.800
Why, I'll tell thee: this is called Pentapolis,

638
00:41:28.800 --> 00:41:31.170
and our king the good Simonides.

639
00:41:31.170 --> 00:41:32.900
The good Simonides, do you call him.

640
00:41:32.900 --> 00:41:36.070
Ay, sir; and he deserves so to be called for his

641
00:41:36.070 --> 00:41:38.700
peaceable reign and good government.

642
00:41:38.700 --> 00:41:40.870
He is a happy king, since he gains from his subjects

643
00:41:40.870 --> 00:41:44.800
the name of good by his government. How far is his

644
00:41:44.800 --> 00:41:47.270
court distant from this shore?

645
00:41:47.270 --> 00:41:53.200
Marry, sir, half a day's journey:

646
00:41:53.200 --> 00:41:56.700
and I'll tell thee, he hath a fair daughter,

647
00:41:56.700 --> 00:41:59.100
and to-morrow is her birth-day; and there be knights

648
00:41:59.100 --> 00:42:01.130
and princes come from all parts of the world to just

649
00:42:01.130 --> 00:42:04.600
and tourney for her love.

650
00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:07.870
Were my fortunes equal to my desires,

651
00:42:07.870 --> 00:42:09.170
I could wish to make one there.

652
00:42:09.170 --> 00:42:11.570
O, sir, things must be as they may; and what a man

653
00:42:11.570 --> 00:42:15.300
may not get, he may lawfully deal for--his wife's soul.

654
00:42:15.300 --> 00:42:20.100
Help, master, help! here's a fish hangs in the net,

655
00:42:20.100 --> 00:42:29.770
like a poor man's right in the law; 'twill hardly come out.

656
00:42:29.770 --> 00:42:33.800
Ha! bots on't, 'tis come at last,

657
00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:37.170
and 'tis turned to a rusty armour.

658
00:42:37.170 --> 00:42:45.070
An armour, friends! I pray you, let me see it.

659
00:42:45.070 --> 00:42:48.470
Thanks, fortune, yet, that, after all my crosses,

660
00:42:48.470 --> 00:42:52.730
Thou givest me somewhat to repair myself;

661
00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:56.170
And though it was mine own, part of my heritage,

662
00:42:56.170 --> 00:42:58.570
Which my dead father did bequeath to me.

663
00:42:58.570 --> 00:43:00.870
With this strict charge, even as he left his life,

664
00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:04.270
'Keep it, my Pericles; it hath been a shield

665
00:43:04.270 --> 00:43:06.930
Twixt me and death;'--and pointed to this brace;--

666
00:43:06.930 --> 00:43:10.630
'For that it saved me, keep it; in like necessity--

667
00:43:10.630 --> 00:43:12.330
The which the gods protect thee from!--

668
00:43:12.330 --> 00:43:15.200
may defend thee.'

669
00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:18.730
It kept where I kept, I so dearly loved it;

670
00:43:18.730 --> 00:43:21.770
Till the rough seas, that spare not any man,

671
00:43:21.770 --> 00:43:27.330
Took it in rage, though calm'd have given't again:

672
00:43:27.330 --> 00:43:32.270
I thank thee for't: my shipwreck now's no ill,

673
00:43:32.270 --> 00:43:33.970
Since I have here my father's gift in's will.

674
00:43:33.970 --> 00:43:35.630
What mean you, sir?

675
00:43:35.630 --> 00:43:38.370
To beg of you, kind friends, this coat of worth,

676
00:43:38.370 --> 00:43:40.270
For it was sometime target to a king;

677
00:43:40.270 --> 00:43:43.330
I know it by this mark. He loved me dearly,

678
00:43:43.330 --> 00:43:45.770
And for his sake I wish the having of it;

679
00:43:45.770 --> 00:43:47.500
And that you'ld guide me to your sovereign's court,

680
00:43:47.500 --> 00:43:49.970
Where with it I may appear a gentleman;

681
00:43:49.970 --> 00:43:51.930
And if that ever my low fortune's better,

682
00:43:51.930 --> 00:43:55.770
I'll pay your bounties; till then rest your debtor.

683
00:43:55.770 --> 00:43:59.230
Why, wilt thou tourney for the lady?

684
00:43:59.230 --> 00:44:02.130
I'll show the virtue I have borne in arms.

685
00:44:02.130 --> 00:44:07.370
Why, do 'e take it, and the gods give thee good on't!

686
00:44:07.370 --> 00:44:13.200
Ay, but hark you, my friend; 'twas we that made up

687
00:44:13.200 --> 00:44:15.130
this garment through the rough seams of the waters:

688
00:44:15.130 --> 00:44:19.300
there are certain condolements, certain vails.

689
00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:21.530
I hope, sir, if you thrive, you'll remember from

690
00:44:21.530 --> 00:44:22.570
whence you had it.

691
00:44:22.570 --> 00:44:23.870
Believe 't, I will.

692
00:44:23.870 --> 00:44:26.600
By your furtherance I am clothed in steel;

693
00:44:26.600 --> 00:44:29.070
And, spite of all the rapture of the sea,

694
00:44:29.070 --> 00:44:30.800
This jewel holds his building on my arm:

695
00:44:30.800 --> 00:44:33.230
Unto thy value I will mount myself

696
00:44:33.230 --> 00:44:35.200
Upon a courser, whose delightful steps

697
00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:37.030
Shall make the gazer joy to see him tread.

698
00:44:37.030 --> 00:44:39.800
Only, my friend, I yet am unprovided

699
00:44:39.800 --> 00:44:41.200
Of a pair of bases.

700
00:44:41.200 --> 00:44:44.130
We'll sure provide: thou shalt have my best gown to

701
00:44:44.130 --> 00:44:47.730
make thee a pair; and I'll bring thee to the court myself.

702
00:44:47.730 --> 00:44:50.930
Then honour be but equal to my will,

703
00:44:50.930 --> 00:44:58.330
This day I'll rise, or else add ill to ill.

704
00:45:06.130 --> 00:45:10.830
