705
00:45:26.530 --> 00:45:28.330
Are the knights ready to begin the triumph?

706
00:45:28.330 --> 00:45:29.600
They are, my liege;

707
00:45:29.600 --> 00:45:31.730
And stay your coming to present themselves.

708
00:45:31.730 --> 00:45:34.500
Return them, we are ready; and our daughter,

709
00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:36.670
In honour of whose birth these triumphs are,

710
00:45:36.670 --> 00:45:39.800
Sits here, like beauty's child, whom nature gat

711
00:45:39.800 --> 00:45:43.570
For men to see, and seeing wonder at.

712
00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:46.500
It pleaseth you, my royal father, to express

713
00:45:46.500 --> 00:45:49.130
My commendations great, whose merit's less.

714
00:45:49.130 --> 00:45:50.830
It's fit it should be so; for princes are

715
00:45:50.830 --> 00:45:55.170
A model which heaven makes like to itself:

716
00:45:55.170 --> 00:45:58.200
As jewels lose their glory if neglected,

717
00:45:58.200 --> 00:46:02.400
So princes their renowns if not respected.

718
00:46:04.570 --> 00:46:05.930
'Tis now your honour, daughter, to entertain

719
00:46:05.930 --> 00:46:08.870
The labour of each knight in his device.

720
00:46:08.870 --> 00:46:11.970
Which, to preserve mine honour, I'll perform.

721
00:46:12.270 --> 00:46:16.270
Who is the first that doth prefer himself?

722
00:46:16.270 --> 00:46:20.600
A knight of Sparta, my renowned father;

723
00:46:20.600 --> 00:46:22.800
And the device he bears upon his shield

724
00:46:22.800 --> 00:46:27.300
Is a black Ethiope reaching at the sun

725
00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:30.070
The word, 'Lux tua vita mihi.'

726
00:46:30.070 --> 00:46:32.500
He loves you well that holds his life of you.

727
00:46:36.130 --> 00:46:39.130
Who is the second that presents himself?

728
00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:43.430
A prince of Macedon, my royal father;

729
00:46:43.430 --> 00:46:45.370
And the device he bears upon his shield

730
00:46:45.370 --> 00:46:50.200
Is an arm'd knight that's conquer'd by a lady;

731
00:46:50.200 --> 00:46:53.170
The motto thus, in Spanish,

732
00:46:53.170 --> 00:46:58.830
'Piu por dulzura que por fuerza.'

733
00:46:58.830 --> 00:47:07.400
Ah, May gentleness, not force, win me the day.

734
00:47:07.400 --> 00:47:09.630
And what's the third?

735
00:47:09.630 --> 00:47:11.300
The third of Antioch;

736
00:47:11.300 --> 00:47:14.030
And his device, a wreath of chivalry;

737
00:47:14.030 --> 00:47:17.670
The word, 'Me pompae provexit apex.'

738
00:47:17.670 --> 00:47:21.070
Desire to gain renoun hath set me on

739
00:47:25.530 --> 00:47:27.630
This is the fourth.

740
00:47:27.630 --> 00:47:31.600
A burning torch that's turned upside down;

741
00:47:31.600 --> 00:47:35.130
The word, 'Quod me alit, me extinguit.'

742
00:47:35.130 --> 00:47:39.170
Which shows that beauty hath his power and will,

743
00:47:39.170 --> 00:47:45.230
It can as well inflame as it can kill.

744
00:47:45.230 --> 00:47:49.830
The fifth, an hand environed with clouds,

745
00:47:49.830 --> 00:47:54.370
Holding out gold that's by the touchstone tried;

746
00:47:54.370 --> 00:47:59.170
The motto thus, 'Sic spectanda fides.'

747
00:47:59.170 --> 00:48:02.970
Thus can you try unlasting faithfulness.

748
00:48:32.830 --> 00:48:34.770
And what's the sixth and last,

749
00:48:34.770 --> 00:48:36.030
the which the knight himself

750
00:48:36.030 --> 00:48:39.900
With such a graceful courtesy deliver'd?

751
00:48:39.900 --> 00:48:44.070
He seems to be a stranger; but his present is

752
00:48:44.070 --> 00:48:48.970
A wither'd branch, that's only green at top;

753
00:48:48.970 --> 00:48:55.830
The motto, 'In hac spe vivo.'

754
00:48:55.830 --> 00:48:57.000
A pretty moral;

755
00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:00.130
In this hope, I live.

756
00:49:00.970 --> 00:49:03.170
From the dejected state wherein he is,

757
00:49:03.170 --> 00:49:07.070
He hopes by you his fortunes yet may flourish.

758
00:49:07.070 --> 00:49:09.070
He had need mean better than his outward show

759
00:49:09.070 --> 00:49:11.470
Can any way speak in his just commend;

760
00:49:11.470 --> 00:49:13.430
For by his rusty outside he appears

761
00:49:13.430 --> 00:49:17.470
To have practised more the whipstock than the lance.

762
00:49:17.470 --> 00:49:19.000
He well may be a stranger, for he comes

763
00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.800
To an honour'd triumph strangely furnished.

764
00:49:21.800 --> 00:49:23.830
And on set purpose let his armour rust

765
00:49:23.830 --> 00:49:26.470
Until this day, to scour it in the dust.

766
00:49:26.470 --> 00:49:30.170
Opinion's but a fool, that makes us scan

767
00:49:30.170 --> 00:49:33.700
The outward habit by the inward man.

768
00:49:34.670 --> 00:49:36.500
But stay, the knights are coming: we will withdraw

769
00:49:36.500 --> 00:49:38.600
Into the gallery.

770
00:49:41.700 --> 00:49:50.070
(â™ª music and the sound of a  crowd)

771
00:50:02.570 --> 00:50:05.070
(horses hooves and chanting crowds)

772
00:50:14.770 --> 00:50:17.170


773
00:50:19.470 --> 00:50:20.730
Knights,

774
00:50:20.730 --> 00:50:23.970
To say you're welcome were superfluous.

775
00:50:23.970 --> 00:50:25.430
To place upon the volume of your deeds,

776
00:50:25.430 --> 00:50:27.930
As in a title-page, your worth in arms,

777
00:50:27.930 --> 00:50:30.630
Were more than you expect, or more than's fit,

778
00:50:30.630 --> 00:50:33.570
Since every worth in show commends itself.

779
00:50:33.570 --> 00:50:37.170
Prepare for mirth, for mirth becomes a feast:

780
00:50:37.170 --> 00:50:44.070
You are princes and my guests.

781
00:50:44.070 --> 00:50:46.930
But you, my knight and guest;

782
00:50:46.930 --> 00:50:48.470
To whom this wreath of victory I give,

783
00:50:48.470 --> 00:50:51.030
And crown you king of this day's happiness.

784
00:50:51.030 --> 00:50:53.000
'Tis more by fortune, lady, than by merit.

785
00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:56.200
Call it by what you will, the day is yours;

786
00:50:56.200 --> 00:50:58.670
And here, I hope, is none that envies it.

787
00:51:02.800 --> 00:51:05.000
In framing an artist, art hath thus decreed,

788
00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:08.200
To make some good, but others to exceed;

789
00:51:08.200 --> 00:51:10.900
And you are her labour'd scholar.

790
00:51:10.900 --> 00:51:14.230
Come, queen o' the feast,--

791
00:51:14.230 --> 00:51:18.930
For, daughter, so you are,--

792
00:51:29.630 --> 00:51:31.330
here take your place:

793
00:51:31.330 --> 00:51:33.800
Marshal the rest, as they deserve their grace.

794
00:51:33.800 --> 00:51:36.600
We are honour'd much by good Simonides.

795
00:51:36.600 --> 00:51:39.170
Your presence glads our days: honour we love;

796
00:51:39.170 --> 00:51:42.530
For who hates honour hates the gods above.

797
00:51:55.800 --> 00:51:59.000
Sir, yonder is your place.

798
00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:00.530
Some other is more fit.

799
00:52:00.530 --> 00:52:02.230
Contend not, sir; for we are gentlemen

800
00:52:02.230 --> 00:52:04.030
That neither in our hearts nor outward eyes

801
00:52:04.030 --> 00:52:07.030
Envy the great nor do the low despise.

802
00:52:07.030 --> 00:52:08.370
You are right courteous knights.

803
00:52:08.370 --> 00:52:11.200
Sit, sir, sit.

804
00:52:28.330 --> 00:52:31.430
By Jove, I wonder, that is king of thoughts,

805
00:52:31.430 --> 00:52:35.030
These cates resist me, he but thought upon.

806
00:52:35.030 --> 00:52:38.130
By Juno, that is queen of marriage,

807
00:52:38.130 --> 00:52:41.800
All viands that I eat do seem unsavoury.

808
00:52:41.800 --> 00:52:48.800
Wishing him my meat. Sure, he's a gallant gentleman.

809
00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:50.470
He's but a country gentleman;

810
00:52:50.470 --> 00:52:53.270
Has done no more than other knights have done;

811
00:52:53.270 --> 00:52:58.070
Has broken a staff or so; so let it pass.

812
00:52:58.070 --> 00:53:01.970
To me he seems like diamond to glass.

813
00:53:01.970 --> 00:53:05.630
Yon king's to me like to my father's picture,

814
00:53:05.630 --> 00:53:08.270
Which tells me in that glory once he was;

815
00:53:08.270 --> 00:53:11.070
Had princes sit, like stars, about his throne,

816
00:53:11.070 --> 00:53:13.770
And he the sun, for them to reverence;

817
00:53:13.770 --> 00:53:16.100
None that beheld him, but, like lesser lights,

818
00:53:16.100 --> 00:53:19.170
Did vail their crowns to his supremacy:

819
00:53:19.170 --> 00:53:23.570
Where now his son's like a glow-worm in the night,

820
00:53:23.570 --> 00:53:27.770
The which hath fire in darkness, none in light:

821
00:53:27.770 --> 00:53:32.600
Whereby I see that Time's the king of men,

822
00:53:32.600 --> 00:53:35.400
He's both their parent, and he is their grave,

823
00:53:35.400 --> 00:53:40.400
And gives them what he will, not what they crave.

824
00:53:47.230 --> 00:53:49.100
What, are you merry, knights?

825
00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:52.430
Who can be other in this royal presence?

826
00:53:52.430 --> 00:53:54.530
Here, with a cup that's stored unto the brim,--

827
00:53:54.530 --> 00:53:59.930
As you do love, fill to your mistress' lips,--

828
00:54:02.430 --> 00:54:05.070
We drink this health to you.

829
00:54:05.070 --> 00:54:06.800
We thank your grace.

830
00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:21.730
Yet pause awhile:

831
00:54:21.730 --> 00:54:24.130
Yon knight doth sit too melancholy,

832
00:54:24.130 --> 00:54:25.400
As if the entertainment in our court

833
00:54:25.400 --> 00:54:27.800
Had not a show might countervail his worth.

834
00:54:27.800 --> 00:54:30.400
Note it not you, Thaisa?

835
00:54:30.400 --> 00:54:32.200
What is't to me, my father?

836
00:54:32.200 --> 00:54:33.200
O, attend, my daughter:

837
00:54:33.200 --> 00:54:35.770
Princes in this should live like gods above,

838
00:54:35.770 --> 00:54:37.130
Who freely give to every one that comes

839
00:54:37.130 --> 00:54:39.070
To honour them:

840
00:54:39.070 --> 00:54:42.370
Therefore to make his entertain more sweet,

841
00:54:43.430 --> 00:54:47.970
Here, say we drink this standing-bowl of wine to him.

842
00:54:54.200 --> 00:54:56.000
Alas, my father, it befits not me

843
00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:59.530
Unto a stranger knight to be so bold:

844
00:54:59.530 --> 00:55:02.300
He may my proffer take for an offence,

845
00:55:02.300 --> 00:55:05.030
Since men take women's gifts for impudence.

846
00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:06.000
How!

847
00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:08.700
Do as I bid you, or you'll move me else.

848
00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:13.100
Now, by the gods, he could not please me better.

849
00:55:13.100 --> 00:55:18.130
And furthermore tell him, we desire to know

850
00:55:18.130 --> 00:55:21.670
Of whence he is, his name and parentage.

851
00:55:34.100 --> 00:55:36.430
The king my father, sir, has drunk to you.

852
00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:38.270
I thank him.

853
00:55:38.270 --> 00:55:41.070
Wishing it so much blood unto your life.

854
00:55:41.070 --> 00:55:45.000
I thank both him and you, and pledge him freely.

855
00:55:47.030 --> 00:55:49.270
And further he desires to know of you,

856
00:55:49.270 --> 00:55:52.300
Of whence you are, your name and parentage.

857
00:55:52.300 --> 00:55:56.130
A gentleman of Tyre; my name, Pericles;

858
00:55:56.130 --> 00:55:58.730
My education been in arts and arms;

859
00:55:58.730 --> 00:56:00.130
Who, looking for adventures in the world,

860
00:56:00.130 --> 00:56:03.800
Was by the rough seas reft of ships and men,

861
00:56:03.800 --> 00:56:07.430
And after shipwreck driven upon this shore.

862
00:56:25.230 --> 00:56:28.670
He thanks your grace; names himself Pericles,

863
00:56:28.670 --> 00:56:29.670
A gentleman of Tyre,

864
00:56:29.670 --> 00:56:31.270
Who only by misfortune of the seas

865
00:56:31.270 --> 00:56:34.870
Bereft of ships and men, cast on this shore.

866
00:56:34.870 --> 00:56:38.330
Now, by the gods, I pity his misfortune,

867
00:56:39.170 --> 00:56:41.730
And will awake him from his melancholy.

868
00:56:42.570 --> 00:56:45.130
Come, gentlemen, we sit too long on trifles,

869
00:56:45.130 --> 00:56:48.170
And waste the time, which looks for other revels.

870
00:56:49.570 --> 00:56:52.100
(laughing)

871
00:56:52.500 --> 00:56:54.070
Even in your armours, as you are address'd,

872
00:56:54.070 --> 00:56:56.600
Will very well become a soldier's dance.

873
00:56:58.830 --> 00:57:01.000
I will not have excuse, with saying this

874
00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:04.030
Loud music is too harsh for ladies' heads,

875
00:57:04.030 --> 00:57:06.830
Since they love men in arms as well as beds.

876
00:57:11.070 --> 00:57:22.130
(â™ª music)

877
00:58:43.030 --> 00:58:47.370
So, this was well ask'd,'twas so well perform'd.

878
00:58:49.800 --> 00:58:52.530
Come, sir;

879
00:58:52.530 --> 00:58:56.400
Here is a lady that wants breathing too:

880
00:58:56.400 --> 00:58:57.870
And I have heard, you knights of Tyre

881
00:58:57.870 --> 00:59:00.300
Are excellent in making ladies trip;

882
00:59:01.100 --> 00:59:04.170
And that their measures are as excellent.

883
00:59:04.170 --> 00:59:05.970
In those that practise them they are, my lord.

884
00:59:05.970 --> 00:59:08.400
O, that's as much as you would be denied

885
00:59:08.400 --> 00:59:14.770
Of your fair courtesy.

886
01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:23.270
Unclasp, unclasp:

887
01:02:26.530 --> 01:02:29.530
Thanks, gentlemen, to all; all have done well.

888
01:02:29.530 --> 01:02:34.370
But you the best. Pages and lights,

889
01:02:34.370 --> 01:02:38.370
To conduct these knights unto their several lodgings!

890
01:02:38.370 --> 01:02:41.270
Yours, sir, We have given order to be next our own.

891
01:02:41.270 --> 01:02:42.970
I am at your grace's pleasure.

892
01:02:42.970 --> 01:02:45.230
Princes, it is too late to talk of love;

893
01:02:45.230 --> 01:02:47.900
And that's the mark I know you level at:

894
01:02:47.900 --> 01:02:50.330
Therefore each one betake him to his rest;

895
01:02:50.330 --> 01:02:53.930
To-morrow all for speeding do their best.

896
01:03:25.930 --> 01:03:28.430
No, Escanes, know this of me,

897
01:03:28.430 --> 01:03:31.800
Antiochus from incest lived not free:

898
01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:34.930
For which, the most high gods not minding longer

899
01:03:34.930 --> 01:03:36.870
To withhold the vengeance that they had in store,

900
01:03:36.870 --> 01:03:39.300
Due to this heinous capital offence,

901
01:03:39.300 --> 01:03:42.600
Even in the height and pride of all his glory,

902
01:03:42.600 --> 01:03:45.000
When he was seated in a chariot

903
01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:48.830
Of an inestimable value, and his daughter with him,

904
01:03:48.830 --> 01:03:51.600
A fire from heaven came and shrivell'd up

905
01:03:51.600 --> 01:03:54.900
Their bodies, even to loathing; for they so stunk,

906
01:03:54.900 --> 01:03:58.100
That all those eyes adored them ere their fall

907
01:03:58.100 --> 01:04:01.530
Scorn now their hand should give them burial.

908
01:04:01.530 --> 01:04:04.000
'Twas very strange.

909
01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:06.130
And yet but justice;

910
01:04:06.130 --> 01:04:10.600
for though this king were great, his greatness was no guard

911
01:04:10.600 --> 01:04:15.930
To bar heaven's shaft, but sin had his reward.

912
01:04:15.930 --> 01:04:17.700
'Tis very true.

913
01:04:22.370 --> 01:04:25.230
See, not a man in private conference

914
01:04:25.230 --> 01:04:27.270
Or council has respect with him but he.

915
01:04:27.270 --> 01:04:29.500
It shall no longer grieve without reproof.

916
01:04:29.500 --> 01:04:31.100
And cursed be he that will not second it.

917
01:04:31.100 --> 01:04:32.970
Follow me, then.

918
01:04:38.670 --> 01:04:41.500
Lord Helicane, a word.

919
01:04:41.500 --> 01:04:45.670
With me? and welcome: happy day, my lords.

920
01:04:45.670 --> 01:04:48.330
Know that our griefs are risen to the top,

921
01:04:48.330 --> 01:04:50.570
And now at length they overflow their banks.

922
01:04:50.570 --> 01:04:55.770
Your griefs! for what? wrong not your prince you love.

923
01:04:55.770 --> 01:04:58.700
Wrong not yourself, then, noble Helicane;

924
01:04:58.700 --> 01:05:00.900
But if the prince do live, let us salute him,

925
01:05:00.900 --> 01:05:04.270
Or know what ground's made happy by his breath.

926
01:05:04.270 --> 01:05:09.200
If in the world he live, we'll seek him out;

927
01:05:09.200 --> 01:05:11.600
If in his grave he rest, we'll find him there;

928
01:05:11.600 --> 01:05:14.970
And be resolved he lives to govern us,

929
01:05:14.970 --> 01:05:17.670
Or dead, give's cause to mourn his funeral,

930
01:05:17.670 --> 01:05:21.200
And leave us to our free election.

931
01:05:21.200 --> 01:05:23.730
Whose death indeed's the strongest in our censure:

932
01:05:23.730 --> 01:05:26.400
And knowing this kingdom is without a head,--

933
01:05:26.400 --> 01:05:28.030
Like goodly buildings left without a roof

934
01:05:28.030 --> 01:05:30.600
Soon fall to ruin,--your noble self,

935
01:05:30.600 --> 01:05:33.730
That best know how to rule and how to reign,

936
01:05:33.730 --> 01:05:36.200
We thus submit unto,--our sovereign.

937
01:05:36.200 --> 01:05:41.000
Live, noble Helicane!

938
01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:44.270
By honour's cause, forbear your suffrages:

939
01:05:44.270 --> 01:05:48.200
If that you love Prince Pericles, forbear.

940
01:05:48.200 --> 01:05:50.900
Take I your wish, I leap into the seas,

941
01:05:50.900 --> 01:05:53.870
Where's hourly trouble for a minute's ease.

942
01:05:53.870 --> 01:05:56.270
A twelvemonth longer, let me entreat you

943
01:05:56.270 --> 01:05:59.870
Further to bear the absence of your king:

944
01:05:59.870 --> 01:06:03.330
If in which time expired, he not return,

945
01:06:03.330 --> 01:06:08.670
I shall with aged patience bear your yoke.

946
01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:18.270
But if I cannot win you to this love,

947
01:06:18.270 --> 01:06:24.330
Go search like nobles, like noble subjects,

948
01:06:24.330 --> 01:06:28.430
And in your search spend your adventurous worth;

949
01:06:28.430 --> 01:06:31.670
Whom if you find, and win unto return,

950
01:06:31.670 --> 01:06:35.030
You shall like diamonds sit about his crown.

951
01:06:35.300 --> 01:06:38.730
To wisdom he's a fool that will not yield;

952
01:06:38.730 --> 01:06:41.330
And since Lord Helicane enjoineth us,

953
01:06:41.330 --> 01:06:44.670
We with our travels will endeavour it.

954
01:06:44.670 --> 01:06:51.970
Then you love us, we you, and we'll clasp hands:

955
01:06:56.500 --> 01:07:01.430
When peers thus knit, a kingdom ever stands.

956
01:07:09.130 --> 01:07:12.500
Good morrow to the good Simonides.

957
01:07:12.500 --> 01:07:17.700
Knights, from my daughter this I let you know,

958
01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:20.000
That for this twelvemonth she'll not undertake

959
01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:23.600
A married life.

960
01:07:23.600 --> 01:07:25.300
Her reason to herself is only known,

961
01:07:25.300 --> 01:07:27.430
Which from her by no means can I get.

962
01:07:27.430 --> 01:07:29.970
May we not get access to her, my lord?

963
01:07:29.970 --> 01:07:32.600
'Faith, by no means; she has so strictly tied

964
01:07:32.600 --> 01:07:38.030
Her to her chamber, that 'tis impossible.

965
01:07:38.030 --> 01:07:40.300
One twelve moons more she'll wear Diana's livery;

966
01:07:40.300 --> 01:07:42.430
This by the eye of Cynthia hath she vow'd

967
01:07:42.430 --> 01:07:45.730
And on her virgin honour will not break it.

968
01:07:47.330 --> 01:07:59.500
Loath to bid farewell, we take our leaves.

969
01:07:59.500 --> 01:08:03.700
So, They are well dispatch'd; now to my daughter's letter:

970
01:08:08.270 --> 01:08:11.800
She tells me here, she'd wed the stranger knight,

971
01:08:11.800 --> 01:08:14.070
Or never more to view nor day nor light.

972
01:08:14.070 --> 01:08:16.630
'Tis well, mistress; your choice agrees with mine;

973
01:08:16.630 --> 01:08:22.770
I like that well: nay, how absolute she's in't,

974
01:08:22.770 --> 01:08:27.900
Not minding whether I dislike or no!

975
01:08:27.900 --> 01:08:29.700
Well, I do commend her choice;

976
01:08:29.700 --> 01:08:32.330
And will no longer have it be delay'd.

977
01:08:32.330 --> 01:08:35.130
Soft! here he comes: I must dissemble it.

978
01:08:41.230 --> 01:08:44.000
All fortune to the good Simonides!

979
01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:48.430
To you as much, sir! I am beholding to you

980
01:08:48.430 --> 01:08:50.230
For your sweet music this last night:

981
01:08:50.230 --> 01:08:52.230
I do protest my ears were never better fed

982
01:08:52.230 --> 01:08:54.100
With such delightful pleasing harmony.

983
01:08:54.100 --> 01:08:55.600
It is your grace's pleasure to commend;

984
01:08:55.600 --> 01:08:56.770
Not my desert.

985
01:08:56.770 --> 01:08:58.470
Sir, you are music's master.

986
01:08:58.470 --> 01:09:00.830
The worst of all her scholars, my good lord.

987
01:09:00.830 --> 01:09:02.570
Let me ask you one thing:

988
01:09:02.570 --> 01:09:05.800
What do you think of my daughter, sir?

989
01:09:05.800 --> 01:09:07.730
A most virtuous princess.

990
01:09:07.730 --> 01:09:09.930
And she is fair too, is she not?

991
01:09:09.930 --> 01:09:12.800
As a fair day in summer, wondrous fair.

992
01:09:12.800 --> 01:09:15.300
Sir, my daughter thinks very well of you;

993
01:09:15.300 --> 01:09:17.030
Ay, so well, that you must be her master,

994
01:09:17.030 --> 01:09:19.900
And she will be your scholar: therefore look to it.

995
01:09:19.900 --> 01:09:22.030
I am unworthy for her schoolmaster.

996
01:09:22.030 --> 01:09:30.370
She thinks not so; peruse this writing else.

997
01:09:32.100 --> 01:09:34.500
What's here?

998
01:09:38.230 --> 01:09:41.870
A letter, that she loves the knight of Tyre!

999
01:09:43.570 --> 01:09:48.370
'Tis the king's subtlety to have my life.

1000
01:09:48.370 --> 01:09:52.170
O, seek not to entrap me, gracious lord,

1001
01:09:52.170 --> 01:09:54.070
A stranger and distressed gentleman,

1002
01:09:54.070 --> 01:09:56.430
That never aim'd so high to love your daughter,

1003
01:09:56.430 --> 01:09:59.100
But bent all offices to honour her.

1004
01:09:59.100 --> 01:10:00.770
Thou hast bewitch'd my daughter, and thou art a villain.

1005
01:10:00.770 --> 01:10:03.030
By the gods, I have not:

1006
01:10:03.030 --> 01:10:05.530
Never did thought of mine levy offence;

1007
01:10:05.530 --> 01:10:07.430
Nor never did my actions yet commence

1008
01:10:07.430 --> 01:10:10.270
A deed might gain her love or your displeasure.

1009
01:10:10.270 --> 01:10:11.570
Traitor, thou liest.

1010
01:10:11.570 --> 01:10:12.470
Traitor!

1011
01:10:12.470 --> 01:10:13.400
Ay, traitor.

1012
01:10:13.400 --> 01:10:15.300
Even in his throat--unless it be the king--

1013
01:10:15.300 --> 01:10:17.800
That calls me traitor, I return the lie.

1014
01:10:21.530 --> 01:10:24.230
Now, by the gods, I do applaud his courage.

1015
01:10:24.230 --> 01:10:26.100
My actions are as noble as my thoughts,

1016
01:10:26.100 --> 01:10:28.730
That never relish'd of a base descent.

1017
01:10:28.730 --> 01:10:31.630
I came unto your court for honour's cause,

1018
01:10:31.630 --> 01:10:33.870
And not to be a rebel to her state;

1019
01:10:33.870 --> 01:10:35.370
And he that otherwise accounts of me,

1020
01:10:35.370 --> 01:10:37.600
This sword shall prove he's honour's enemy.

1021
01:10:37.600 --> 01:10:39.300
No?

1022
01:10:39.300 --> 01:10:42.970
Here comes my daughter, she can witness it.

1023
01:10:42.970 --> 01:10:44.200
Then, as you are as virtuous as fair,

1024
01:10:44.200 --> 01:10:46.170
Resolve your angry father, if my tongue

1025
01:10:46.170 --> 01:10:48.170
Did ere solicit, or my hand subscribe

1026
01:10:48.170 --> 01:10:54.270
To any syllable that made love to you.

1027
01:10:54.270 --> 01:10:57.070
Why, sir, say if you had,

1028
01:10:57.070 --> 01:11:01.400
Who takes offence at that would make me glad?

1029
01:11:01.400 --> 01:11:03.770
Yea, mistress, are you so peremptory?

1030
01:11:03.770 --> 01:11:06.000
I am glad on't with all my heart.--

1031
01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:09.000
I'll tame you; I'll bring you in subjection.

1032
01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:10.500
Will you, not having my consent,

1033
01:11:10.500 --> 01:11:12.300
Bestow your love and your affections

1034
01:11:12.300 --> 01:11:14.730
Upon a stranger?

1035
01:11:14.730 --> 01:11:16.330
who, for aught I know,

1036
01:11:16.330 --> 01:11:17.670
May be, nor can I think the contrary,

1037
01:11:17.670 --> 01:11:21.330
As great in blood as I myself.--

1038
01:11:21.330 --> 01:11:24.970
Therefore hear you, mistress; either frame

1039
01:11:24.970 --> 01:11:28.530
Your will to mine,--and you, sir, hear you,

1040
01:11:28.530 --> 01:11:32.130
Either be ruled by me, or I will make you--

1041
01:11:32.130 --> 01:11:34.630
Man and wife:

1042
01:11:34.630 --> 01:11:37.230
Nay, come, your hands and lips must seal it too:

1043
01:11:37.230 --> 01:11:39.770
And being join'd, I'll thus your hopes destroy;

1044
01:11:39.770 --> 01:11:45.600
And for a further grief,--God give you joy!--

1045
01:11:50.230 --> 01:11:51.230
What, are you both pleased?

1046
01:11:51.230 --> 01:11:56.470
Yes, if you love me, sir.

1047
01:11:56.470 --> 01:12:00.430
Even as my life, or blood that fosters it.

1048
01:12:10.630 --> 01:12:13.470
What, are you both agreed?

1049
01:12:13.470 --> 01:12:20.230
Yes, if it please your majesty.

1050
01:12:20.230 --> 01:12:24.430
It pleaseth me so well, that I will see you wed;

1051
01:12:24.430 --> 01:12:27.930
And then with what haste you can get you to bed.

1052
01:12:40.600 --> 01:12:44.130
Now sleep y-slaked hath the rout;

1053
01:12:44.130 --> 01:12:48.270
No din but snores the house about,

1054
01:12:48.270 --> 01:12:50.370
Made louder by the o'er-fed breast

1055
01:12:50.370 --> 01:12:55.000
Of this most pompous marriage-feast.

1056
01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:58.600
The cat, with eyne of burning coal,

1057
01:12:58.600 --> 01:13:00.930
Now crouches fore the mouse's hole;

1058
01:13:00.930 --> 01:13:03.300
And crickets sing at the oven's mouth,

1059
01:13:03.300 --> 01:13:06.870
E'er the blither for their drouth.

1060
01:13:06.870 --> 01:13:10.230
Hymen hath brought the bride to bed.

1061
01:13:10.230 --> 01:13:13.270
Where, by the loss of maidenhead,

1062
01:13:13.270 --> 01:13:18.330
A babe is moulded. Be attent,

1063
01:13:18.330 --> 01:13:22.000
And time that is so briefly spent

1064
01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:25.400
With your fine fancies quaintly eche:

1065
01:13:25.400 --> 01:13:31.500
What's dumb in show I'll plain with speech.

1066
01:13:31.500 --> 01:13:33.870
By many a dern and painful perch

1067
01:13:33.870 --> 01:13:35.900
Of Pericles the careful search,

1068
01:13:35.900 --> 01:13:37.470
By the four opposing coigns

1069
01:13:37.470 --> 01:13:39.170
Which the world together joins,

1070
01:13:39.170 --> 01:13:41.100
Is made with all due diligence

1071
01:13:41.100 --> 01:13:43.400
That horse and sail and high expense

1072
01:13:43.400 --> 01:13:47.470
Can stead the quest. At last from Tyre,

1073
01:13:47.470 --> 01:13:50.400
Fame answering the most strange inquire,

1074
01:13:50.400 --> 01:13:51.770
To the court of King Simonides

1075
01:13:51.770 --> 01:13:56.670
Are letters brought, the tenor these:

1076
01:13:56.670 --> 01:13:59.070
Antiochus and his daughter dead;

1077
01:13:59.070 --> 01:14:00.400
The men of Tyrus on the head

1078
01:14:00.400 --> 01:14:01.930
Of Helicanus would set on

1079
01:14:01.930 --> 01:14:05.330
The crown of Tyre, but he will none:

1080
01:14:05.330 --> 01:14:07.400
The mutiny he there hastes t' oppress;

1081
01:14:07.400 --> 01:14:09.600
Says to 'em, if King Pericles

1082
01:14:09.600 --> 01:14:13.030
Come not home in twice six moons,

1083
01:14:13.030 --> 01:14:14.670
He, obedient to their dooms,

1084
01:14:14.670 --> 01:14:18.900
Will take the crown. The sum of this,

1085
01:14:18.900 --> 01:14:20.400
Brought hither to Pentapolis,

1086
01:14:20.400 --> 01:14:22.130
Y-ravished the regions round,

1087
01:14:22.130 --> 01:14:25.070
And every one with claps can sound,

1088
01:14:25.070 --> 01:14:27.030
'Our heir-apparent is a king!

1089
01:14:27.030 --> 01:14:31.100
Who dream'd, who thought of such a thing?'

1090
01:14:31.100 --> 01:14:34.030
Brief, he must hence depart to Tyre:

1091
01:14:34.030 --> 01:14:37.500
His queen with child makes her desire--

1092
01:14:37.500 --> 01:14:41.670
Which who shall cross?--along to go:

1093
01:14:41.670 --> 01:14:45.230
Omit we all their dole and woe:

1094
01:14:45.230 --> 01:14:47.870
Lychorida, her nurse, she takes,

1095
01:14:47.870 --> 01:14:51.170
And so to sea.

1096
01:14:52.100 --> 01:14:56.530
Their vessel shakes on Neptune's billow; half the flood

1097
01:14:56.530 --> 01:14:59.000
Hath their keel cut: but fortune's mood

1098
01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:02.270
Varies again; the grisly north

1099
01:15:02.270 --> 01:15:05.000
Disgorges such a tempest forth,

1100
01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:07.270
That, as a duck for life that dives,

1101
01:15:07.270 --> 01:15:10.400
So up and down the poor ship drives:

1102
01:15:10.400 --> 01:15:12.030
The lady shrieks, and well-a-near

1103
01:15:12.030 --> 01:15:15.970
Does fall in travail with her fear:

1104
01:15:15.970 --> 01:15:18.600
And what ensues in this fell storm

1105
01:15:18.600 --> 01:15:20.800
Shall for itself itself perform.

1106
01:15:20.800 --> 01:15:23.500
I nill relate, action may

1107
01:15:23.500 --> 01:15:24.970
Conveniently the rest convey;

1108
01:15:24.970 --> 01:15:28.630
Which might not what by me is told.

1109
01:15:28.630 --> 01:15:30.730
In your imagination hold

1110
01:15:30.730 --> 01:15:34.370
This stage the ship, upon whose deck

1111
01:15:34.370 --> 01:15:39.170
The sea-tost Pericles appears to speak.

1112
01:15:39.170 --> 01:15:43.670
Thou god of this great vast, rebuke these surges,

1113
01:15:43.670 --> 01:15:49.070
Which wash both heaven and hell; and thou, that hast

1114
01:15:49.070 --> 01:15:52.770
Upon the winds command, bind them in brass,

1115
01:15:52.770 --> 01:15:56.070
Having call'd them from the deep!

1116
01:15:56.070 --> 01:16:01.270
O, still thy deafening, dreadful thunders;

1117
01:16:01.270 --> 01:16:05.300
gently quench thy nimble, sulphurous flashes!

1118
01:16:05.300 --> 01:16:11.400
O, how, Lychorida, How does my queen?

1119
01:16:11.400 --> 01:16:13.170
Thou stormest venomously;

1120
01:16:13.170 --> 01:16:17.330
Wilt thou spit all thyself? The seaman's whistle

1121
01:16:17.330 --> 01:16:19.570
Is as a whisper in the ears of death,

1122
01:16:19.570 --> 01:16:27.100
Unheard. Lychorida!--Lucina,

1123
01:16:27.100 --> 01:16:29.170
O Divinest patroness, and midwife gentle

1124
01:16:29.170 --> 01:16:32.870
To those that cry by night, convey thy deity

1125
01:16:32.870 --> 01:16:37.170
Aboard our dancing boat; make swift the pangs

1126
01:16:37.170 --> 01:16:39.200
Of my queen's travails!

1127
01:16:53.600 --> 01:16:56.370
Here is a thing too young for such a place,

1128
01:16:56.370 --> 01:16:58.170
Who, if it had conceit, would die,

1129
01:16:58.170 --> 01:17:02.100
as I am like to do: take in your arms this piece

1130
01:17:02.100 --> 01:17:05.100
Of your dead queen.

1131
01:17:06.570 --> 01:17:10.070
How, how, Lychorida!

1132
01:17:10.070 --> 01:17:14.230
Patience, good sir; do not assist the storm.

1133
01:17:14.230 --> 01:17:18.300
Here's all that is left living of your queen,

1134
01:17:18.300 --> 01:17:21.230
A little daughter: for the sake of it,

1135
01:17:21.230 --> 01:17:23.930
Be manly, and take comfort.

1136
01:17:23.930 --> 01:17:28.370
O you gods!

1137
01:17:28.370 --> 01:17:30.800
Why do you make us love your goodly gifts,

1138
01:17:30.800 --> 01:17:35.870
And snatch them straight away? We here below

1139
01:17:35.870 --> 01:17:39.970
Recall not what we give, and therein may

1140
01:17:39.970 --> 01:17:41.730
Use honour with you.

1141
01:17:41.730 --> 01:17:44.200
Patience, good sir,

1142
01:17:44.200 --> 01:17:47.430
Even for this charge.

1143
01:18:00.270 --> 01:18:03.430
Now, mild may be thy life!

1144
01:18:03.430 --> 01:18:07.370
For a more blustrous birth had never babe:

1145
01:18:07.370 --> 01:18:10.330
Quiet and gentle thy conditions!

1146
01:18:10.330 --> 01:18:13.070
for thou art the rudeliest welcome to this world

1147
01:18:13.070 --> 01:18:18.670
That ever was prince's child. Happy what follows!

1148
01:18:20.970 --> 01:18:23.430
Thou hast as chiding a nativity

1149
01:18:23.430 --> 01:18:27.070
As fire, air, water, earth, and heaven can make,

1150
01:18:27.070 --> 01:18:29.670
To herald thee from the womb: poor itch of nature

1151
01:18:35.930 --> 01:18:40.000
even at the first thy loss is more than can thy portage quit,

1152
01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:48.170
With all thou canst find here. Now, the good gods

1153
01:18:48.170 --> 01:18:51.700
Throw their best eyes upon't!

1154
01:18:58.930 --> 01:19:00.800
What courage, sir? God save you!

1155
01:19:00.800 --> 01:19:04.270
Courage enough: I do not fear the flaw;

1156
01:19:04.270 --> 01:19:07.270
It hath done to me the worst. Yet, for the love

1157
01:19:07.270 --> 01:19:13.770
Of this poor infant, this fresh-new sea-farer,

1158
01:19:13.770 --> 01:19:18.230
I would it would be quiet.

1159
01:19:22.100 --> 01:19:25.570
Slack the bolins there! Thou wilt not, wilt thou?

1160
01:19:25.570 --> 01:19:27.730
Blow, and split thyself.

1161
01:19:27.730 --> 01:19:32.170
But sea-room, an the brine and cloudy billow kiss the moon,

1162
01:19:32.170 --> 01:19:34.100
I care not.

1163
01:19:37.430 --> 01:19:41.530
Sir, your queen must overboard: the sea works high,

1164
01:19:41.530 --> 01:19:43.770
the wind is loud, and will not lie till the ship be

1165
01:19:43.770 --> 01:19:45.600
cleared of the dead.

1166
01:19:45.600 --> 01:19:48.400
That's your superstition.

1167
01:19:48.400 --> 01:19:51.170
Pardon us, sir; with us at sea it hath been still observed:

1168
01:19:51.170 --> 01:19:53.170
and we are strong in custom.

1169
01:19:53.170 --> 01:19:59.130
Therefore briefly yield her; for she must overboard straight.

1170
01:19:59.130 --> 01:20:05.830
As you think meet. Most wretched queen!

1171
01:20:14.670 --> 01:20:16.600
Here she lies, sir.

1172
01:20:32.330 --> 01:20:36.070
A terrible childbed hast thou had, my dear;

1173
01:20:36.070 --> 01:20:39.500
No light, no fire: the unfriendly elements

1174
01:20:39.500 --> 01:20:44.470
Forgot thee utterly: nor have I time

1175
01:20:44.470 --> 01:20:47.330
To give thee hallow'd to thy grave, but straight

1176
01:20:47.330 --> 01:20:51.370
Must cast thee, scarcely coffin'd, in the ooze;

1177
01:20:51.370 --> 01:20:53.470
Where, for a monument upon thy bones,

1178
01:20:53.470 --> 01:20:56.700
And e'er-remaining lamps, the belching whale

1179
01:20:56.700 --> 01:20:59.700
And humming water must o'erwhelm thy corpse,

1180
01:20:59.700 --> 01:21:02.000
Lying with simple shells.

1181
01:21:08.300 --> 01:21:13.100
O Lychorida,

1182
01:21:13.100 --> 01:21:17.730
Bid Nestor bring me spices, ink and paper,

1183
01:21:17.730 --> 01:21:20.030
My casket and my jewels; and bid Nicander

1184
01:21:20.030 --> 01:21:24.500
Bring me the satin coffer: lay the babe upon the pillow:

1185
01:21:25.830 --> 01:21:27.130
hie thee, whiles I say

1186
01:21:27.130 --> 01:21:32.370
A priestly farewell to her: suddenly, woman.

1187
01:21:39.700 --> 01:21:44.030
Sir, we have a chest beneath the hatches,

1188
01:21:44.030 --> 01:21:45.830
caulked and bitumed ready.

1189
01:21:45.830 --> 01:21:51.030
I thank thee. Mariner, say what coast is this?

1190
01:21:51.030 --> 01:21:52.630
We are near Tarsus.

1191
01:21:52.630 --> 01:21:54.230
Thither, gentle mariner.

1192
01:21:54.230 --> 01:21:57.400
Alter thy course for Tyre. When canst thou reach it?

1193
01:21:57.400 --> 01:21:59.470
By break of day, if the wind cease.

1194
01:21:59.470 --> 01:22:02.200
O, make for Tarsus!

1195
01:22:02.200 --> 01:22:05.200
There will I visit Cleon, for the babe

1196
01:22:05.200 --> 01:22:08.370
Cannot hold out to Tyrus:

1197
01:22:08.370 --> 01:22:12.970
there I'll leave it at careful nursing.

1198
01:22:12.970 --> 01:22:15.730
Go thy ways, good mariner:

1199
01:22:15.730 --> 01:22:18.130
I'll bring the body presently.

1200
01:22:54.130 --> 01:23:01.000
Philemon, ho!

1201
01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:02.370
Doth my lord call?

1202
01:23:02.370 --> 01:23:04.800
Get fire and meat for these poor men:

1203
01:23:04.800 --> 01:23:08.400
'T has been a turbulent and stormy night.

1204
01:23:13.070 --> 01:23:15.170
I have been in many; but such a night as this,

1205
01:23:15.170 --> 01:23:17.970
Till now, I ne'er endured.

1206
01:23:17.970 --> 01:23:21.730
Your master will be dead ere you return;

1207
01:23:21.730 --> 01:23:24.330
There's nothing can be minister'd to nature

1208
01:23:24.330 --> 01:23:25.900
That can recover him.

1209
01:23:39.500 --> 01:23:44.000
Give this to the 'pothecary,

1210
01:23:44.000 --> 01:23:49.130
And tell me how it works.

1211
01:23:56.770 --> 01:23:57.530
Good morrow.

1212
01:23:57.530 --> 01:23:58.730
Good morrow to your lordship.

1213
01:23:58.730 --> 01:24:03.630
Gentlemen,

1214
01:24:03.630 --> 01:24:05.600
Why do you stir so early?

1215
01:24:05.600 --> 01:24:06.900
Sir,

1216
01:24:06.900 --> 01:24:08.970
Our lodgings, standing bleak upon the sea,

1217
01:24:08.970 --> 01:24:11.500
Shook as the earth did quake;

1218
01:24:11.500 --> 01:24:13.770
The very principals did seem to rend,

1219
01:24:13.770 --> 01:24:17.530
And all-to topple: pure surprise and fear

1220
01:24:17.530 --> 01:24:19.170
Made me to quit the house.

1221
01:24:19.170 --> 01:24:21.300
That is the cause we trouble you so early;

1222
01:24:21.300 --> 01:24:22.900
'Tis not our husbandry.

1223
01:24:22.900 --> 01:24:24.400
O, you say well.

1224
01:24:24.400 --> 01:24:26.070
But I much marvel that your lordship, having

1225
01:24:26.070 --> 01:24:29.000
Rich tire about you, should at these early hours

1226
01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:31.470
Shake off the golden slumber of repose.

1227
01:24:31.470 --> 01:24:32.600
'Tis most strange,

1228
01:24:32.600 --> 01:24:34.400
Nature should be so conversant with pain,

1229
01:24:34.400 --> 01:24:35.900
Being thereto not compell'd.

1230
01:24:35.900 --> 01:24:36.830
I hold it ever,

1231
01:24:36.830 --> 01:24:39.900
Virtue and cunning were endowments greater

1232
01:24:39.900 --> 01:24:43.000
Than nobleness and riches: careless heirs

1233
01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:46.000
May the two latter darken and expend;

1234
01:24:46.000 --> 01:24:48.370
But immortality attends the former.

1235
01:24:48.370 --> 01:24:53.330
Making a man a god. 'Tis known,

1236
01:24:53.330 --> 01:24:56.500
I ever have studied physic, through which secret art,

1237
01:24:56.500 --> 01:25:00.530
By turning o'er authorities, I have,

1238
01:25:00.530 --> 01:25:03.230
Together with my practise, made familiar

1239
01:25:03.230 --> 01:25:06.600
To me and to my aid the blest infusions

1240
01:25:06.600 --> 01:25:11.400
That dwell in vegetives, in metals, stones;

1241
01:25:11.400 --> 01:25:12.900
And I can speak of the disturbances

1242
01:25:12.900 --> 01:25:16.870
That nature works, and of her cures; which doth give me

1243
01:25:16.870 --> 01:25:18.900
A more content in course of true delight

1244
01:25:18.900 --> 01:25:22.430
Than to be thirsty after tottering honour,

1245
01:25:22.430 --> 01:25:25.570
Or tie my treasure up in silken bags,

1246
01:25:25.570 --> 01:25:28.070
To please the fool and death.

1247
01:25:28.070 --> 01:25:30.470
Your honour has through Ephesus pour'd forth

1248
01:25:30.470 --> 01:25:32.830
Your charity, and hundreds call themselves

1249
01:25:32.830 --> 01:25:34.570
Your creatures, who by you have been restored:

1250
01:25:34.570 --> 01:25:37.730
And not your knowledge, your personal pain,

1251
01:25:37.730 --> 01:25:40.930
but even your purse, still open, hath built Lord Cerimon

1252
01:25:40.930 --> 01:25:44.330
Such strong renown as time shall ne'er raise.

1253
01:25:45.570 --> 01:25:47.700
So; lift there.

1254
01:25:47.700 --> 01:25:50.070
What is that?

1255
01:25:50.070 --> 01:25:53.500
Sir, even now did the sea toss upon our shore this chest:

1256
01:25:53.500 --> 01:25:55.070
'Tis of some wreck.

1257
01:25:55.070 --> 01:25:57.100
Set 't down, let's look upon't.

1258
01:25:57.100 --> 01:25:59.000
'Tis like a coffin, sir.

1259
01:25:59.000 --> 01:26:01.230
Whate'er it be, 'Tis wondrous heavy.

1260
01:26:01.230 --> 01:26:03.100
Wrench it open straight:

1261
01:26:03.100 --> 01:26:05.270
If the sea's stomach be o'ercharged with gold,

1262
01:26:05.270 --> 01:26:09.230
'Tis a good constraint of fortune it belches upon us.

1263
01:26:09.230 --> 01:26:11.000
'Tis so, my lord.

1264
01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:13.470
How close 'tis caulk'd and bitumed!

1265
01:26:13.470 --> 01:26:15.430
Did the sea cast it up?

1266
01:26:15.430 --> 01:26:17.270
I never saw so huge a billow, sir,

1267
01:26:17.270 --> 01:26:19.300
As toss'd it upon shore.

1268
01:26:19.300 --> 01:26:20.430
Wrench it open;

1269
01:26:34.700 --> 01:26:38.400
Soft! it smells most sweetly in my sense.

1270
01:26:38.400 --> 01:26:39.900
A delicate odour.

1271
01:26:39.900 --> 01:26:45.200
As ever hit my nostril. So, up with it.

1272
01:26:52.730 --> 01:26:57.800
O you most potent gods! what's here? a corse!

1273
01:26:57.800 --> 01:27:01.500
Most strange!

1274
01:27:01.500 --> 01:27:05.700
Shrouded in cloth of state; balm'd and entreasured

1275
01:27:05.700 --> 01:27:11.630
With full bags of spices! A passport too!

1276
01:27:15.170 --> 01:27:20.100
Apollo, perfect me in the characters!

1277
01:27:20.100 --> 01:27:23.330
'Here I give to understand,

1278
01:27:23.330 --> 01:27:25.870
If e'er this coffin drive a-land,

1279
01:27:25.870 --> 01:27:30.600
I, King Pericles, have lost this queen,

1280
01:27:30.600 --> 01:27:33.570
worth all our mundane cost.

1281
01:27:33.570 --> 01:27:37.430
Who finds her, give her burying;

1282
01:27:37.430 --> 01:27:40.270
She was the daughter of a king:

1283
01:27:40.270 --> 01:27:43.430
Besides this treasure for a fee,

1284
01:27:43.430 --> 01:27:47.070
The gods requite his charity!'

1285
01:27:47.700 --> 01:27:51.000
O Pericles, If thou livest, thou hast a heart

1286
01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:59.770
That even cracks for woe! This chanced tonight.

1287
01:27:59.770 --> 01:28:00.800
Most likely, sir.

1288
01:28:00.800 --> 01:28:02.800
Nay, certainly to-night;

1289
01:28:02.800 --> 01:28:09.130
For look how fresh she looks! They were too rough

1290
01:28:09.130 --> 01:28:12.930
That threw her in the sea. Make a fire within:

1291
01:28:12.930 --> 01:28:17.200
Fetch hither all my boxes in my closet.

1292
01:28:21.100 --> 01:28:24.430
Death may usurp on nature many hours,

1293
01:28:24.430 --> 01:28:26.570
And yet the fire of life kindle again

1294
01:28:26.570 --> 01:28:29.770
The o'erpress'd spirits. I read of some Egyptians

1295
01:28:29.770 --> 01:28:32.670
Who after four hourse death, have raised impoverished spirits

1296
01:28:32.670 --> 01:28:36.170
Like to this, unto their former heatlh.

1297
01:28:36.170 --> 01:28:42.730
Well said, well said; the fire and cloths.

1298
01:28:42.730 --> 01:28:46.330
The rough and woeful music that we have,

1299
01:28:46.330 --> 01:28:49.400
Cause it to sound, beseech you.

1300
01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:19.970
The viol once more:

1301
01:31:18.370 --> 01:31:26.230
how thou stirr'st, thou block!

1302
01:31:26.230 --> 01:31:31.330
The music there!--I pray you, give her air.

1303
01:31:31.330 --> 01:31:32.930
Gentlemen.

1304
01:31:32.930 --> 01:31:39.370
This queen will live: nature awakes; a warmth

1305
01:31:39.370 --> 01:31:41.070
Breathes out of her: she hath not been entranced

1306
01:31:41.070 --> 01:31:46.500
Above five hours: see how she gins to blow

1307
01:31:46.500 --> 01:31:48.500
Into life's flower again!

1308
01:31:48.500 --> 01:31:51.200
The heavens, Through you, increase our wonder

1309
01:31:51.200 --> 01:31:54.100
and set up your fame forever.

1310
01:31:54.100 --> 01:31:55.630
She is alive; behold,

1311
01:31:55.630 --> 01:31:59.100
Her eyelids, cases to those heavenly jewels

1312
01:31:59.100 --> 01:32:00.700
Which Pericles hath lost,

1313
01:32:00.700 --> 01:32:06.400
Begin to part their fringes of bright gold;

1314
01:32:06.400 --> 01:32:08.330
The diamonds of a most praised water

1315
01:32:08.330 --> 01:32:13.230
Doth appear, to make the world twice rich.

1316
01:32:13.230 --> 01:32:18.730
Live, and make us weep to hear your fate, fair creature,

1317
01:32:18.730 --> 01:32:21.930
Rare as you seem to be.

1318
01:32:43.100 --> 01:32:44.200
O dear Diana,

1319
01:32:44.200 --> 01:32:54.100
Where am I? Where's my lord? What world is this?

1320
01:32:54.530 --> 01:32:56.300
Is not this strange?

1321
01:32:56.300 --> 01:32:57.170
Most rare.

1322
01:32:57.170 --> 01:32:58.630
Hush, my gentle neighbours!

1323
01:32:58.630 --> 01:33:01.430
Lend me your hands; to the next chamber bear her.

1324
01:33:01.430 --> 01:33:04.300
Get linen: now this matter must be look'd to,

1325
01:33:04.300 --> 01:33:09.770
For her relapse is mortal. Come, come;

1326
01:33:12.900 --> 01:33:16.630
And AEsculapius guide us!

1327
01:33:53.800 --> 01:33:57.400
Most honour'd Cleon, I must needs be gone;

1328
01:33:57.400 --> 01:33:59.200
My twelve months are expired, and Tyrus stands

1329
01:33:59.200 --> 01:34:01.770
In a litigious peace. You, and your lady,

1330
01:34:01.770 --> 01:34:04.170
Take from my heart all thankfulness!

1331
01:34:04.170 --> 01:34:05.970
The gods make up the rest upon you!

1332
01:34:05.970 --> 01:34:08.930
Your strokes of fortune, though they hurt you mortally,

1333
01:34:08.930 --> 01:34:10.830
Yet glance full woundingly on us.

1334
01:34:10.830 --> 01:34:14.600
O your sweet queen! That the strict fates had pleased you

1335
01:34:14.600 --> 01:34:15.630
had brought her hither,

1336
01:34:15.630 --> 01:34:17.770
To have bless'd mine eyes with her!

1337
01:34:17.770 --> 01:34:20.700
We cannot but obey the powers above us.

1338
01:34:20.700 --> 01:34:25.700
Could I rage and roar  as doth the sea she lies in,

1339
01:34:25.700 --> 01:34:28.230
yet the end must be as 'tis.

1340
01:34:37.230 --> 01:34:39.330
My gentle babe Marina, whom,

1341
01:34:39.330 --> 01:34:42.170
For she was born at sea, I have named so,

1342
01:34:42.170 --> 01:34:44.400
here I charge your charity withal,

1343
01:34:44.400 --> 01:34:47.570
leaving her the infant of your care; beseeching you

1344
01:34:47.570 --> 01:34:49.400
To give her princely training, that she may be

1345
01:34:49.400 --> 01:34:50.770
Manner'd as she is born.

1346
01:34:50.770 --> 01:34:53.170
Fear not, my lord, but think

1347
01:34:53.170 --> 01:34:55.530
Your grace, that fed my country with your corn,

1348
01:34:55.530 --> 01:34:58.070
For which the people's prayers still fall upon you,

1349
01:34:58.070 --> 01:35:00.600
Must in your child be thought on.

1350
01:35:00.600 --> 01:35:04.000
If neglection should therein make me vile, the common body,

1351
01:35:04.000 --> 01:35:07.530
By you relieved, would force me to my duty:

1352
01:35:07.530 --> 01:35:10.430
But if to that my nature need a spur,

1353
01:35:10.430 --> 01:35:13.330
The gods revenge it upon me and mine,

1354
01:35:13.330 --> 01:35:15.030
To the end of generation!

1355
01:35:15.030 --> 01:35:16.470
I believe you;

1356
01:35:16.470 --> 01:35:18.170
Your honour and your goodness teach me to't,

1357
01:35:18.170 --> 01:35:24.570
Without your vows. Till she be married, madam,

1358
01:35:24.570 --> 01:35:26.970
By bright Diana, whom we honour,

1359
01:35:26.970 --> 01:35:31.200
all unscissor'd shall this hair of mine remain,

1360
01:35:31.200 --> 01:35:38.330
Though I show ill in't. So I take my leave.

1361
01:35:42.500 --> 01:35:44.200
Good madam, make me blessed in your care

1362
01:35:44.200 --> 01:35:45.330
In bringing up my child.

1363
01:35:45.330 --> 01:35:46.500
I have one myself,

1364
01:35:46.500 --> 01:35:49.000
Who shall not be more dear to my respect

1365
01:35:49.000 --> 01:35:50.730
Than yours, my lord.

1366
01:35:50.730 --> 01:35:53.330
Madam, my thanks and prayers.

1367
01:35:53.330 --> 01:35:56.300
We'll bring your grace e'en to the edge o' the shore,

1368
01:35:56.300 --> 01:35:59.270
Then give you up to the mask'd Neptune

1369
01:35:59.270 --> 01:36:01.200
and the gentlest winds of heaven.

1370
01:36:01.200 --> 01:36:02.370
I will embrace your offer.

1371
01:36:02.370 --> 01:36:07.130
Come, dearest madam. O, no tears, Lychorida, no tears:

1372
01:36:07.130 --> 01:36:09.730
Look to your little mistress, on whose grace

1373
01:36:09.730 --> 01:36:15.170
You may depend hereafter. Come, my lord.

1374
01:36:56.600 --> 01:37:01.670
Madam, this letter, and some certain jewels,

1375
01:37:01.670 --> 01:37:02.400
Lay with you in your coffer:

1376
01:37:02.400 --> 01:37:05.530
which are now at your command.

1377
01:37:05.530 --> 01:37:11.600
Know you the character? It is my lord's.

1378
01:37:32.970 --> 01:37:35.770
That I was shipp'd at sea, I well remember,

1379
01:37:35.770 --> 01:37:41.100
Even on my eaning time; but whether there deliver'd,

1380
01:37:41.100 --> 01:37:44.800
by the holy gods, I cannot rightly say.

1381
01:37:55.930 --> 01:37:58.030
But since King Pericles,

1382
01:37:58.030 --> 01:38:02.370
My wedded lord, I ne'er shall see again,

1383
01:38:02.370 --> 01:38:07.170
A vestal livery will I take me to,

1384
01:38:07.170 --> 01:38:09.830
And never more have joy.

1385
01:38:09.830 --> 01:38:13.100
Madam, if this you purpose as ye speak,

1386
01:38:13.100 --> 01:38:16.900
Diana's temple is not distant far,

1387
01:38:16.900 --> 01:38:20.870
Where you may abide till your date expire.

1388
01:38:20.870 --> 01:38:24.400
Moreover, if you please, a niece of mine

1389
01:38:24.400 --> 01:38:27.930
Shall there attend you.

1390
01:38:27.930 --> 01:38:31.400
My recompense is thanks, that's all;

1391
01:38:31.400 --> 01:38:35.500
Yet my good will is great, though the gift small.

1392
01:38:48.830 --> 01:38:50.130


1393
01:38:52.530 --> 01:38:56.170
Imagine Pericles arrived at Tyre,

1394
01:38:56.170 --> 01:38:59.870
Welcomed and settled to his own desire.

1395
01:38:59.870 --> 01:39:02.700
His woeful queen we leave at Ephesus,

1396
01:39:02.700 --> 01:39:07.500
Unto Diana there a votaress.

1397
01:39:07.500 --> 01:39:11.670
Now to Marina bend your mind,

1398
01:39:11.670 --> 01:39:13.930
Whom our fast-growing scene must find

1399
01:39:13.930 --> 01:39:17.530
At Tarsus, and by Cleon train'd

1400
01:39:17.530 --> 01:39:19.930
In music, letters; who hath gain'd

1401
01:39:19.930 --> 01:39:22.770
Of education all the grace,

1402
01:39:22.770 --> 01:39:27.300
Which makes her both the heart and place of general wonder.

1403
01:39:27.300 --> 01:39:31.730
But, alack, That monster envy, oft the wrack

1404
01:39:31.730 --> 01:39:35.000
Of earned praise, Marina's life

1405
01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:39.000
Seeks to take off by treason's knife.

1406
01:39:39.000 --> 01:39:43.400
And in this kind our Cleon hath one daughter,

1407
01:39:43.400 --> 01:39:45.900
and a wench full grown,

1408
01:39:45.900 --> 01:39:50.730
Even ripe for marriage-rite; this maid hight Philoten:

1409
01:39:50.730 --> 01:39:52.970
and it is said for certain in our story,

1410
01:39:52.970 --> 01:39:56.470
she would ever with Marina be:

1411
01:39:56.470 --> 01:39:59.470
Be't when she weaved the sleided silk

1412
01:39:59.470 --> 01:40:04.200
With fingers long, small, white as milk;

1413
01:40:04.200 --> 01:40:07.100
Or when she would with sharp needle wound

1414
01:40:07.100 --> 01:40:09.630
The cambric, which she made more sound

1415
01:40:09.630 --> 01:40:12.130
By hurting it; or when to the lute

1416
01:40:12.130 --> 01:40:15.830
She sung, and made the night-bird mute,

1417
01:40:15.830 --> 01:40:18.630
That still records with moan;

1418
01:40:18.630 --> 01:40:21.770
or when She would with rich and constant pen

1419
01:40:21.770 --> 01:40:25.170
Vail to her mistress Dian;

1420
01:40:25.170 --> 01:40:28.630
Still, this Philoten contends in skill

1421
01:40:28.630 --> 01:40:32.670
With absolute Marina:

1422
01:40:32.670 --> 01:40:37.330
so with the dove of Paphos might the crow

1423
01:40:37.330 --> 01:40:41.400
Vie feathers white. Marina gets all praises,

1424
01:40:41.400 --> 01:40:43.770
which are paid as debts,

1425
01:40:43.770 --> 01:40:47.900
And not as given. This so darks

1426
01:40:47.900 --> 01:40:51.370
In Philoten all graceful marks,

1427
01:40:51.370 --> 01:40:53.900
That Cleon's wife, with envy rare,

1428
01:40:53.900 --> 01:40:58.070
A present murderer does prepare for good Marina,

1429
01:40:58.070 --> 01:41:03.200
that her daughter might stand peerless by this slaughter.

1430
01:41:03.200 --> 01:41:06.230
The sooner her vile thoughts to stead,

1431
01:41:06.230 --> 01:41:09.400
Lychorida, our nurse, is dead:

1432
01:41:09.400 --> 01:41:11.670
And cursed Dionyza hath

1433
01:41:11.670 --> 01:41:17.430
The pregnant instrument of wrath prest for this blow.

1434
01:41:17.430 --> 01:41:18.800
The unborn event

1435
01:41:18.800 --> 01:41:21.600
I do commend to your content:

1436
01:41:21.600 --> 01:41:24.200
Only I carry winged time

1437
01:41:24.200 --> 01:41:28.030
Post on the lame feet of my rhyme;

1438
01:41:28.030 --> 01:41:30.030
Which never could I so convey,

1439
01:41:30.030 --> 01:41:35.200
Unless your thoughts went on my way.

1440
01:41:35.200 --> 01:41:37.500
Dionyza does appear,

1441
01:41:37.500 --> 01:41:41.200
With Leonine, a murderer.

1442
01:41:43.000 --> 01:41:50.100
Thy oath remember; thou hast sworn to do't:

1443
01:41:50.100 --> 01:41:52.830
'Tis but a blow, which never shall be known.

1444
01:41:52.830 --> 01:41:55.000
Thou canst not do a thing in the world so soon,

1445
01:41:55.000 --> 01:41:58.130
To yield thee so much profit. Let not conscience,

1446
01:41:58.130 --> 01:42:01.600
Which is but cold, nor flaming love thy bosom enslaved

1447
01:42:01.600 --> 01:42:03.630
too nicely; nor let pity,

1448
01:42:03.630 --> 01:42:06.400
which even women have cast off, melt thee,

1449
01:42:06.400 --> 01:42:10.800
but be a soldier to thy purpose.

1450
01:42:10.800 --> 01:42:20.470
I will do't; but yet she is a goodly creature.

1451
01:42:20.470 --> 01:42:24.230
The fitter, then, the gods should have her.

1452
01:42:24.230 --> 01:42:27.800
Here she comes weeping for her only nurses' death.

1453
01:42:27.800 --> 01:42:30.370
Thou art resolved?

1454
01:42:30.370 --> 01:42:33.730
I am resolved.

1455
01:42:33.730 --> 01:42:40.630
No, I will rob Tellus of her weed,

1456
01:42:40.630 --> 01:42:43.700
To strew thy green with flowers:

1457
01:42:53.830 --> 01:42:57.730
the yellows, blues, the purple violets, and marigolds,

1458
01:42:57.730 --> 01:43:04.700
Shall as a carpet hang upon thy grave,

1459
01:43:04.700 --> 01:43:13.200
While summer-days do last. Ay me! poor maid,

1460
01:43:13.200 --> 01:43:16.500
Born in a tempest, when my mother died,

1461
01:43:16.500 --> 01:43:18.270
This world to me is like a lasting storm,

1462
01:43:18.270 --> 01:43:21.500
Whirring me from my friends.

1463
01:43:21.500 --> 01:43:25.870
How now, Marina! why do you keep alone?

1464
01:43:25.870 --> 01:43:28.900
How chance my daughter is not with you?

1465
01:43:28.900 --> 01:43:31.570
Do not consume your blood with sorrowing:

1466
01:43:31.570 --> 01:43:38.170
What, have you a nurse of me. Lord, how your favour's changed

1467
01:43:38.170 --> 01:43:41.130
With this unprofitable woe!

1468
01:43:41.130 --> 01:43:44.870
Come, give me your flowers, On the sea march'nt.

1469
01:43:44.870 --> 01:43:47.900
Walk with Leonine; the air is quick there,

1470
01:43:47.900 --> 01:43:50.300
And it pierces and sharpens the stomach.

1471
01:43:50.300 --> 01:43:53.070
Come Leonine, take her by the arm, walk with her.

1472
01:43:53.070 --> 01:43:54.170
No, I pray you;

1473
01:43:54.170 --> 01:43:56.030
I'll not bereave you of your servant.

1474
01:43:56.030 --> 01:43:58.800
Come, come;

1475
01:43:58.800 --> 01:44:02.100
I love the king your father, and yourself,

1476
01:44:02.100 --> 01:44:05.730
With more than foreign heart. We every day

1477
01:44:05.730 --> 01:44:08.830
Expect him here: when he shall come and see

1478
01:44:08.830 --> 01:44:12.370
Our paragon to all reports thus blasted,

1479
01:44:12.370 --> 01:44:15.270
He will repent the breadth of his great voyage;

1480
01:44:15.270 --> 01:44:17.530
Blame both my lord and me, that we have taken

1481
01:44:17.530 --> 01:44:22.070
No care to your best courses. Go, I pray you,

1482
01:44:22.070 --> 01:44:25.970
Walk, and be cheerful once again;

1483
01:44:25.970 --> 01:44:29.070
reserve that excellent complexion, which did steal

1484
01:44:29.070 --> 01:44:33.100
The eyes of young and old. Care not for me

1485
01:44:33.100 --> 01:44:35.170
I can go home alone.

1486
01:44:35.170 --> 01:44:37.330
Well, I will go;

1487
01:44:37.330 --> 01:44:39.070
But yet I have no desire to it.

1488
01:44:39.070 --> 01:44:42.330
Come, come, I know 'tis good for you.

1489
01:44:42.330 --> 01:44:45.670
Walk half an hour, Leonine, at the least:

1490
01:44:45.670 --> 01:44:47.330
Remember what I have said.

1491
01:44:47.330 --> 01:44:48.870
I warrant you, madam.

1492
01:44:48.870 --> 01:44:51.230
I'll leave you, my sweet lady, for a while:

1493
01:44:51.230 --> 01:44:54.170
Pray, walk softly, do not heat your blood:

1494
01:44:54.170 --> 01:44:59.370
What! I must have care of you.

1495
01:44:59.370 --> 01:45:04.730
My thanks, sweet madam.

1496
01:45:16.800 --> 01:45:18.730
Is this wind westerly that blows?

1497
01:45:18.730 --> 01:45:19.870
South-west.

1498
01:45:23.300 --> 01:45:25.370
When I was born, the wind was north.

1499
01:45:25.370 --> 01:45:26.730
Was't so?

1500
01:45:26.730 --> 01:45:29.900
My father, as nurse said, did never fear,

1501
01:45:29.900 --> 01:45:33.530
But cried 'Good seaman!' to the sailors, galling

1502
01:45:33.530 --> 01:45:35.730
His kingly hands, haling ropes;

1503
01:45:35.730 --> 01:45:37.670
And, clasping to the mast, endured a sea

1504
01:45:37.670 --> 01:45:39.930
That almost burst the deck.

1505
01:45:39.930 --> 01:45:42.670
When was this?

1506
01:45:42.670 --> 01:45:46.070
When I was born:

1507
01:45:46.070 --> 01:45:49.430
Never was wind nor waves more violent;

1508
01:45:49.430 --> 01:45:52.370
And from the ladder-tackle washes off a canvas-climber.

1509
01:45:52.370 --> 01:45:55.200
'Ha!' says one, 'wilt out?'

1510
01:45:55.200 --> 01:45:56.870
And with a dropping industry they skip

1511
01:45:56.870 --> 01:45:59.600
From stem to stern: the boatswain whistles,

1512
01:45:59.600 --> 01:46:02.230
and the master calls, and trebles their confusion.

1513
01:46:02.230 --> 01:46:05.300
Come, say your prayers.

1514
01:46:05.300 --> 01:46:07.930
What mean you?

1515
01:46:07.930 --> 01:46:09.870
If you require a little space for prayer,

1516
01:46:09.870 --> 01:46:14.730
I grant it: pray; but be not tedious,

1517
01:46:14.730 --> 01:46:16.330
For the gods are quick of ear, and I am sworn

1518
01:46:16.330 --> 01:46:18.100
To do my work with haste.

1519
01:46:18.100 --> 01:46:19.970
Why will you kill me?

1520
01:46:19.970 --> 01:46:22.430
To satisfy my lady.

1521
01:46:22.430 --> 01:46:24.700
Why would she have me kill'd?

1522
01:46:24.700 --> 01:46:26.230
Now, as I can remember, by my troth,

1523
01:46:26.230 --> 01:46:28.700
I never did her hurt in all my life:

1524
01:46:28.700 --> 01:46:30.770
I never spake bad word, nor did ill turn

1525
01:46:30.770 --> 01:46:33.100
To any living creature: believe me, la,

1526
01:46:33.100 --> 01:46:35.030
I never kill'd a mouse, nor hurt a fly:

1527
01:46:35.030 --> 01:46:36.500
I trod upon a worm against my will,

1528
01:46:36.500 --> 01:46:39.870
But I wept for it. How have I offended,

1529
01:46:39.870 --> 01:46:41.470
Wherein my death might yield her any profit,

1530
01:46:41.470 --> 01:46:44.830
Or my life imply her any danger?

1531
01:46:44.830 --> 01:46:47.930
My commission Is not to reason of the deed, but do it.

1532
01:46:47.930 --> 01:46:50.300
You will not do't for all the world, I hope.

1533
01:46:50.300 --> 01:46:52.170
You are well favour'd, and your looks foreshow

1534
01:46:52.170 --> 01:46:55.170
You have a gentle heart. I saw you lately,

1535
01:46:55.170 --> 01:46:57.500
When you caught hurt in parting two that fought:

1536
01:46:57.500 --> 01:47:01.870
Good sooth, it show'd well in you: do so now:

1537
01:47:01.870 --> 01:47:05.070
Your lady seeks my life; come you between,

1538
01:47:05.070 --> 01:47:07.800
And save poor me, the weaker.

1539
01:47:07.800 --> 01:47:10.500
I am sworn,

1540
01:47:10.500 --> 01:47:12.370
And will dispatch.

1541
01:47:15.730 --> 01:47:18.300
Hold, villain!

1542
01:47:18.300 --> 01:47:20.330
A prize! a prize!

1543
01:47:20.330 --> 01:47:23.100
Half-part, mates, half-part.

1544
01:47:23.100 --> 01:47:26.630
Come, let's have her aboard suddenly.

1545
01:47:26.630 --> 01:47:32.230
These roguing thieves serve the great pirate Valdes;

1546
01:47:32.230 --> 01:47:38.300
And they have seized Marina. Let her go:

1547
01:47:38.300 --> 01:47:40.630
There's no hope she will return.

1548
01:47:40.630 --> 01:47:44.600
I'll swear she's dead,

1549
01:47:44.600 --> 01:47:51.170
And thrown into the sea. But I'll see further:

1550
01:47:51.170 --> 01:47:54.430
Perhaps they will but please themselves upon her,

1551
01:47:54.430 --> 01:47:58.630
Not carry her aboard. If she remain,

1552
01:47:58.630 --> 01:48:05.900
Whom they have ravish'd must by me be slain.

1553
01:48:52.200 --> 01:48:54.000
Boult!

1554
01:48:54.000 --> 01:48:57.100
Sir?

1555
01:48:57.370 --> 01:49:02.130
Search the market narrowly; Mytilene is full of gallants.

1556
01:49:02.130 --> 01:49:06.530
We lost too much money this mart by being too wenchless.

1557
01:49:06.530 --> 01:49:08.430
We were never so much out of creatures.

1558
01:49:08.430 --> 01:49:10.330
We have but poor three,

1559
01:49:10.330 --> 01:49:12.270
and they can do no more than they can do;

1560
01:49:12.270 --> 01:49:16.300
and they with continual action are even as good as rotten.

1561
01:49:16.300 --> 01:49:19.800
Therefore let's have fresh ones, whate'er we pay for them.

1562
01:49:19.800 --> 01:49:23.670
If there be not a conscience to be used in every trade,

1563
01:49:23.670 --> 01:49:25.000
we shall never prosper.

1564
01:49:25.000 --> 01:49:29.330
Thou sayest true: 'tis not our bringing up of poor bastards,

1565
01:49:29.330 --> 01:49:32.830
--as, I think, I have brought up some eleven--

1566
01:49:32.830 --> 01:49:36.770
Ay, to eleven; and brought them down again.

1567
01:49:36.770 --> 01:49:38.470
But shall I search the market?

1568
01:49:38.470 --> 01:49:42.300
What else, man? The stuff we have, a strong wind

1569
01:49:42.300 --> 01:49:47.700
will blow it to pieces, they are so pitifully sodden.

1570
01:49:47.700 --> 01:49:55.100
Thou sayest true; they're too unwholesome, o' conscience.

1571
01:49:55.100 --> 01:49:58.170
The poor Transylvanian is dead,

1572
01:49:58.170 --> 01:50:00.000
that lay with the little baggage.

1573
01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:05.530
Ay, she quickly pooped him; she made him roast-meat for worms.

1574
01:50:05.530 --> 01:50:09.270
But I'll go search the market.

1575
01:50:13.800 --> 01:50:16.530
Three or four thousand chequins were as pretty a

1576
01:50:16.530 --> 01:50:22.530
proportion to live quietly, and so give over.

1577
01:50:22.530 --> 01:50:25.770
Why to give over, I pray you? is it a shame to get

1578
01:50:25.770 --> 01:50:27.730
when we are old?

1579
01:50:27.730 --> 01:50:31.100
O, our credit comes not in like the commodity,

1580
01:50:31.100 --> 01:50:34.400
nor the commodity wages not with the danger:

1581
01:50:34.400 --> 01:50:37.770
therefore, if in our youths we could pick up

1582
01:50:37.770 --> 01:50:43.670
some pretty estate, 'twere not amiss to keep our door hatched.

1583
01:50:43.670 --> 01:50:48.930
Besides, the sore terms we stand upon with the gods

1584
01:50:48.930 --> 01:50:51.970
will be strong with us for giving over.

1585
01:50:51.970 --> 01:50:53.900
Come, other sorts offend as well as we.

1586
01:50:53.900 --> 01:50:59.170
As well as we! ay, and better too; we offend worse.

1587
01:50:59.170 --> 01:51:02.900
Neither is our profession any trade;

1588
01:51:02.900 --> 01:51:07.630
it's no calling. But here comes Boult.

1589
01:51:07.630 --> 01:51:14.900
Come your ways. My masters, you say she's a virgin?

1590
01:51:14.900 --> 01:51:19.100
O, sir, we doubt it not.

1591
01:51:20.800 --> 01:51:24.030
Master, I have gone through for this piece, you see:

1592
01:51:24.030 --> 01:51:27.730
if you like her, so; if not, I have lost my earnest.

1593
01:51:29.700 --> 01:51:32.730
Boult, has she any qualities?

1594
01:51:32.730 --> 01:51:34.130
She has a good face, speaks well,

1595
01:51:34.130 --> 01:51:37.270
and has excellent good clothes: there's no further necessity

1596
01:51:37.270 --> 01:51:45.570
of qualities can make her be refused.

1597
01:51:45.570 --> 01:51:47.330
What's her price, Boult?

1598
01:51:47.330 --> 01:51:52.730
I cannot be bated one doit of a thousand pieces.

1599
01:51:54.900 --> 01:52:00.900
Well, follow me, my masters,

1600
01:52:00.900 --> 01:52:04.700
you shall have your money presently.

1601
01:52:04.700 --> 01:52:08.970
Wife, take her in; instruct her what she has to do,

1602
01:52:08.970 --> 01:52:12.870
that she may not be raw in her entertainment.

1603
01:52:25.970 --> 01:52:33.030
Boult, take you the marks of her, the colour of her hair,

1604
01:52:33.030 --> 01:52:36.800
complexion, height, age, with warrant of her virginity;

1605
01:52:36.800 --> 01:52:38.270
and cry 'He that will give most shall

1606
01:52:38.270 --> 01:52:43.270
have her first.' Such a maidenhead were no cheap thing,

1607
01:52:43.270 --> 01:52:46.770
if men were as they have been.

1608
01:52:46.770 --> 01:52:50.630
Get this done as I command you.

1609
01:52:50.630 --> 01:52:53.730
Performance shall follow.

1610
01:52:53.730 --> 01:52:55.930
Alack that Leonine was so slack, so slow!

1611
01:52:55.930 --> 01:52:59.930
He should have struck, not spoke; or that these pirates,

1612
01:52:59.930 --> 01:53:03.630
Not enough barbarous, had not o'erboard thrown me

1613
01:53:03.630 --> 01:53:07.770
For to seek my mother!

1614
01:53:07.770 --> 01:53:11.070
Why lament you, pretty one?

1615
01:53:11.070 --> 01:53:12.500
That I am pretty.

1616
01:53:13.070 --> 01:53:16.330
Come, the gods have done their part in you.

1617
01:53:16.330 --> 01:53:18.330
I accuse them not.

1618
01:53:18.330 --> 01:53:22.000
You are light into my hands, where you are like to live.

1619
01:53:22.000 --> 01:53:23.370
The more my fault To scape his hands

1620
01:53:23.370 --> 01:53:24.600
where I was like to die.

1621
01:53:24.600 --> 01:53:25.630
Ay, and you shall live in pleasure.

1622
01:53:25.630 --> 01:53:26.830
No.

1623
01:53:26.830 --> 01:53:29.470
Yes, indeed shall you, and taste gentlemen of all fashions:

1624
01:53:29.470 --> 01:53:32.770
you shall fare well; you shall have the

1625
01:53:32.770 --> 01:53:39.330
difference of all complexions. What! do you stop your ears?

1626
01:53:39.330 --> 01:53:40.930
Are you a woman?

1627
01:53:40.930 --> 01:53:42.300
What would you have me be, an I be not a woman?

1628
01:53:42.300 --> 01:53:44.400
An honest woman, or not a woman.

1629
01:53:44.400 --> 01:53:50.070
Marry, whip thee, gosling: I think I shall have

1630
01:53:50.070 --> 01:53:56.630
something to do with you. Come, you're a young foolish sapling,

1631
01:53:56.630 --> 01:53:58.830
and must be bowed as I would have you.

1632
01:53:58.830 --> 01:54:01.830
The gods defend me!

1633
01:54:01.830 --> 01:54:04.600
If it please the gods to defend you by men,

1634
01:54:04.600 --> 01:54:10.230
then men must comfort you, men must feed you,

1635
01:54:10.800 --> 01:54:14.270
men to stir you up.

1636
01:54:18.330 --> 01:54:20.330
Boult's returned.

1637
01:54:20.830 --> 01:54:24.370
How now, sir, hast thou cried her through the market?

1638
01:54:24.370 --> 01:54:27.770
I have cried her almost to the number of her hairs;

1639
01:54:27.770 --> 01:54:31.970
I have drawn her picture with my voice.

1640
01:54:31.970 --> 01:54:33.400
And I prithee tell me, how dost thou find the inclination

1641
01:54:33.400 --> 01:54:35.530
of the people, especially of the younger sort?

1642
01:54:35.530 --> 01:54:37.230
'Faith, they listened to me as they would have

1643
01:54:37.230 --> 01:54:39.630
hearkened to their father's testament.

1644
01:54:39.630 --> 01:54:40.970
There was a Spaniard's mouth so watered,

1645
01:54:40.970 --> 01:54:43.630
that he went to bed to her very description.

1646
01:54:43.630 --> 01:54:44.700
We shall have him here to-morrow

1647
01:54:44.700 --> 01:54:46.730
with his best ruff on.

1648
01:54:46.730 --> 01:54:49.730
To-night, to-night. But, mistress,

1649
01:54:49.730 --> 01:54:52.200
Do you know the French knight that cowers i' the hams?

1650
01:54:52.200 --> 01:54:53.670
Who, Monsieur Veroles?

1651
01:54:53.670 --> 01:54:56.730
Ay, he: he offered to cut a caper at the proclamation;

1652
01:54:56.730 --> 01:54:58.800
but he made a groan at it, and swore

1653
01:54:58.800 --> 01:55:01.600
he would see her to-morrow.

1654
01:55:03.730 --> 01:55:06.330
Well, well; as for him, he brought his disease hither:

1655
01:55:06.330 --> 01:55:07.730
here he does but repair it.

1656
01:55:07.730 --> 01:55:11.070
I know he will come in our shadow,

1657
01:55:11.070 --> 01:55:14.700
to scatter his crowns in the sun.

1658
01:55:14.700 --> 01:55:18.100
Well, if we had of every nation a traveller,

1659
01:55:18.100 --> 01:55:22.770
we should lodge them with this sign.

1660
01:55:22.770 --> 01:55:27.430
Pray you, come hither awhile.

1661
01:55:31.770 --> 01:55:42.330
You have fortunes coming upon you. Mark me:

1662
01:55:44.130 --> 01:55:45.430
you must seem to do that fearfully

1663
01:55:45.430 --> 01:55:47.270
which you commit willingly,

1664
01:55:47.270 --> 01:55:49.170
despise profit where you have most gain.

1665
01:55:49.170 --> 01:55:53.770
To weep that you live as ye do makes pity in your lovers:

1666
01:55:53.770 --> 01:55:56.870
seldom but that pity begets you a good opinion,

1667
01:55:56.870 --> 01:56:03.870
and that opinion a mere profit. I understand you not.

1668
01:56:03.870 --> 01:56:06.700
O, take her home, mistress, take her home:

1669
01:56:06.700 --> 01:56:08.500
these blushes of hers must be quenched

1670
01:56:08.500 --> 01:56:10.130
with some present practise.

1671
01:56:10.130 --> 01:56:12.400
Thou sayest true, i' faith;

1672
01:56:12.400 --> 01:56:16.030
for your bride goes to that with shame

1673
01:56:16.030 --> 01:56:19.570
which is her way to go with warrant.

1674
01:56:19.570 --> 01:56:23.300
'Faith, some do, and some do not. But, mistress,

1675
01:56:23.300 --> 01:56:25.300
if I have bargained for the joint,--

1676
01:56:25.300 --> 01:56:28.330
Thou mayst cut a morsel off the spit.

1677
01:56:28.330 --> 01:56:29.600
I may so.

1678
01:56:29.600 --> 01:56:36.230
Who should deny it? Come, young one, I like the

1679
01:56:36.230 --> 01:56:38.200
manner of your garments well.

1680
01:56:38.200 --> 01:56:41.030
Ay, by my faith, they shall not be changed yet.

1681
01:56:41.030 --> 01:56:45.470
Boult, spend thou that in the town: report what a

1682
01:56:45.470 --> 01:56:49.630
sojourner we have; you'll lose nothing by custom.

1683
01:56:49.630 --> 01:56:50.570
When nature flamed this piece,

1684
01:56:50.570 --> 01:56:51.870
she meant thee a good turn;

1685
01:56:51.870 --> 01:56:54.430
therefore say what a paragon she is,

1686
01:56:54.430 --> 01:56:58.370
and thou hast the harvest out of thine own report.

1687
01:56:58.370 --> 01:57:01.770
I warrant you, mistress, thunder shall not so awake

1688
01:57:01.770 --> 01:57:06.070
the beds of eels as my giving out her beauty

1689
01:57:06.070 --> 01:57:12.070
stir up the lewdly-inclined. I'll bring home some to-night.

1690
01:57:14.400 --> 01:57:17.870
Come your ways; follow me.

1691
01:57:17.870 --> 01:57:20.900
If fires be hot, knives sharp, or waters deep,

1692
01:57:20.900 --> 01:57:25.200
Untied I still my virgin knot will keep.

1693
01:57:25.200 --> 01:57:29.330
Diana, aid my purpose!

1694
01:57:29.330 --> 01:57:33.100
What have we to do with Diana?

1695
01:57:33.100 --> 01:57:37.170
Pray you, will you go with us?

1696
01:57:58.100 --> 01:58:01.000
Why, are you foolish? Can it be undone?

1697
01:58:01.000 --> 01:58:05.370
O Dionyza, such a piece of slaughter

1698
01:58:05.370 --> 01:58:07.400
The sun and moon ne'er look'd upon!

1699
01:58:07.400 --> 01:58:08.870
I think you'll turn a child again.

1700
01:58:08.870 --> 01:58:11.170
Were I chief lord of all this spacious world,

1701
01:58:11.170 --> 01:58:15.370
I'ld give it to undo the deed. O lady,

1702
01:58:15.370 --> 01:58:18.130
Much less in blood than virtue, yet a princess

1703
01:58:18.130 --> 01:58:19.700
To equal any single crown o' the earth

1704
01:58:19.700 --> 01:58:25.870
I' the justice of compare! O villain Leonine!

1705
01:58:25.870 --> 01:58:29.100
Whom thou hast poison'd too:

1706
01:58:29.100 --> 01:58:30.800
If thou hadst drunk to him, 't had been a kindness

1707
01:58:30.800 --> 01:58:33.500
Becoming well thy fact: what canst thou say

1708
01:58:33.500 --> 01:58:36.230
When noble Pericles shall demand his child?

1709
01:58:36.230 --> 01:58:41.000
That she is dead. Nurses are not the fates,

1710
01:58:41.000 --> 01:58:45.030
To foster it, nor ever to preserve.

1711
01:58:45.030 --> 01:58:50.430
She died at night; I'll say so. Who can cross it?

1712
01:58:50.430 --> 01:58:52.130
Unless you play the pious innocent,

1713
01:58:52.130 --> 01:58:53.530
And for an honest attribute cry out

1714
01:58:53.530 --> 01:58:56.200
'She died by foul play.'

1715
01:58:56.200 --> 01:59:02.800
O, go to. Well, well,

1716
01:59:02.800 --> 01:59:07.030
Of all the faults beneath the heavens,

1717
01:59:07.030 --> 01:59:08.670
The gods do like this worst.

1718
01:59:08.670 --> 01:59:09.770
Be one of those that think

1719
01:59:09.770 --> 01:59:11.670
The petty wrens of Tarsus will fly hence,

1720
01:59:11.670 --> 01:59:14.170
And open this to Pericles.

1721
01:59:14.170 --> 01:59:17.530
I shame to think of what a noble strain you are,

1722
01:59:17.530 --> 01:59:20.600
And of how coward a spirit.

1723
01:59:20.600 --> 01:59:21.830
To such proceeding

1724
01:59:21.830 --> 01:59:23.300
Who ever but his approbation gave,

1725
01:59:23.300 --> 01:59:24.900
And not his prime consent,

1726
01:59:24.900 --> 01:59:28.770
he did not flow from honourable sources.

1727
01:59:29.970 --> 01:59:32.700
Be it so, then:

1728
01:59:35.700 --> 01:59:39.030
Yet none does know, but you, how she came dead,

1729
01:59:39.030 --> 01:59:42.170
Nor none can know, Leonine being gone.

1730
01:59:42.170 --> 01:59:46.830
She did disdain my child, and stood between

1731
01:59:46.830 --> 01:59:49.970
Her and her fortunes: none would look on her,

1732
01:59:49.970 --> 01:59:51.600
But cast their gazes on Marina's face;

1733
01:59:51.600 --> 01:59:53.770
Whilst ours was blurted at and held a malkin

1734
01:59:53.770 --> 01:59:58.670
Not worth the time of day. It pierced me through;

1735
01:59:58.670 --> 02:00:01.170
And though you call my course unnatural,

1736
02:00:01.170 --> 02:00:04.400
You not your child well loving, yet I find

1737
02:00:04.400 --> 02:00:07.300
It greets me as an enterprise of kindness

1738
02:00:07.300 --> 02:00:12.170
Perform'd to your sole daughter.

1739
02:00:12.670 --> 02:00:15.070
Heavens forgive it!

1740
02:00:15.070 --> 02:00:17.470
And as for Pericles,

1741
02:00:17.470 --> 02:00:20.700
What should he say? We wept after her hearse,

1742
02:00:20.700 --> 02:00:25.900
And yet we mourn: her monument

1743
02:00:25.900 --> 02:00:29.600
Is almost finish'd, and her epitaphs

1744
02:00:29.600 --> 02:00:32.700
In glittering golden characters express

1745
02:00:32.700 --> 02:00:36.330
A general praise to her, and care in us

1746
02:00:36.330 --> 02:00:41.130
At whose expense 'tis done.

1747
02:00:41.130 --> 02:00:43.370
Thou art like the harpy,

1748
02:00:43.370 --> 02:00:48.430
Which, to betray, dost, with thine angel's face,

1749
02:00:48.430 --> 02:00:50.870
Seize with thine eagle's talons.

1750
02:00:50.870 --> 02:00:52.630
You are like one that superstitiously

1751
02:00:52.630 --> 02:00:57.900
Do swear to the gods that winter kills the flies:

1752
02:00:57.900 --> 02:01:02.900
But yet I know you'll do as I advise.

1753
02:01:13.770 --> 02:01:17.670
Thus time we waste, and long leagues make short;

1754
02:01:17.670 --> 02:01:22.200
Sail seas in cockles, have an wish but for't;

1755
02:01:22.200 --> 02:01:24.330
Making, to take your imagination,

1756
02:01:24.330 --> 02:01:26.970
From bourn to bourn, region to region.

1757
02:01:26.970 --> 02:01:30.770
Where our scenes seem to live. I do beseech you

1758
02:01:30.770 --> 02:01:33.900
To learn of me, who stand i' the gaps to teach you,

1759
02:01:33.900 --> 02:01:35.970
The stages of our story.

1760
02:01:35.970 --> 02:01:40.500
Pericles is now again thwarting the wayward seas,

1761
02:01:40.500 --> 02:01:43.100
Attended on by many a lord and knight.

1762
02:01:43.100 --> 02:01:46.570
To see his daughter, all his life's delight.

1763
02:01:46.570 --> 02:01:48.330
Old Helicanus goes along.

1764
02:01:48.330 --> 02:01:50.470
Behind is left to govern,  if you bear in mind,

1765
02:01:50.470 --> 02:01:52.800
Old Escanes,  whom Helicanus late

1766
02:01:52.800 --> 02:01:56.170
Advanced in time to great and high estate,

1767
02:01:56.170 --> 02:01:59.730
Well-sailing ships and bounteous winds have brought

1768
02:01:59.730 --> 02:02:03.770
This king to Tarsus,--think his pilot thought;

1769
02:02:03.770 --> 02:02:08.330
